{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"primaryCategory":"Faith & Devotion","subcategory":"Theravada Buddhism","audienceTags":["tradition:buddhism","theme:liberation","theme:impermanence","audience:meditation","audience:morning"],"sortPriority":49,"groupingLevels":[],"groupingLabels":[],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/PaliCanon_Suttas.json","supplementalDataPath":null,"languageCode":"en","displayNameEnglish":"Pali Canon Suttas","script":"Latin","isRTL":false,"transliterationAvailable":false,"contentRating":"devotional","sourceId":"paliSuttas","displayName":"Pali Canon Suttas","version":"2.0","language":"English","edition":"Warren, Woodward Public Domain Translations","type":"quotes","browseOrder":"sequence","itemCount":1100,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true},"data":[{"id":"pali-dhammapa-1","text":"Mind is the forerunner of all actions. All deeds are led by mind, created by mind. If one speaks or acts with a corrupt mind, suffering follows, as the wheel follows the hoof of an ox.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Yamaka Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-2","text":"Mind is the forerunner of all actions. All deeds are led by mind, created by mind. If one speaks or acts with a serene mind, happiness follows, as a shadow that never departs.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Yamaka Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-3","text":"He abused me, he beat me, he defeated me, he robbed me — in those who harbor such thoughts, hatred will never cease.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Yamaka Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-4","text":"He abused me, he beat me, he defeated me, he robbed me — in those who do not harbor such thoughts, hatred will quickly cease.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Yamaka Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-5","text":"Heedfulness is the path to the deathless, heedlessness is the path to death. The heedful do not die; the heedless are as if already dead.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Appamada Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-6","text":"More than those who hate you, more than all your enemies, an undisciplined mind does greater harm. More than your mother, more than your father, more than all your family, a well-disciplined mind does greater good.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Chitta Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-7","text":"As a beautiful flower that is colorful but has no fragrance, even so, fruitless is the well-spoken word of one who does not practice it.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Puppha Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-8","text":"Long is the night to him who is awake, long is a mile to him who is tired, long is life to the foolish who do not know the true law.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Bala Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-9","text":"One who has gone to the root of things, who is free from craving, who has finished with the rounds of death and rebirth — that one I call a brahmin.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Pandita Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-10","text":"Better than a thousand hollow words, is one word that brings peace. Better than a thousand hollow verses, is one verse that brings peace.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Sahassa Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-11","text":"Make haste and do what is good; restrain your mind from evil. He who is slow in doing good, his mind delights in evil.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Papa Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-12","text":"All tremble at violence; all fear death. Putting oneself in the place of another, one should not kill nor cause another to kill.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Danda Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-13","text":"How can you find delight and mirth when the world is ever on fire? Lost in darkness, would you not seek the light?","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Jaravagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-dhammapa-14","text":"If you hold yourself dear, then do not taint yourself with evil. For there is no getting happiness easily for one who does an evil deed.","author":"Dhammapada","source":"Dhammapada — Attavagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-majjhima-15","text":"The uninstructed worldling, when touched by a feeling of pain, sorrows, grieves, and laments, beats his breast, becomes distraught.","author":"Majjhima Nikaya","source":"Majjhima Nikaya — Sabbāsava Sutta","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-majjhima-16","text":"When a noble disciple understands suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the way leading to the cessation of suffering — that is called right view.","author":"Majjhima Nikaya","source":"Majjhima Nikaya — Sammaditthi Sutta","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-majjhima-17","text":"It is as if a man were shot by an arrow and his friends went to fetch a physician. But the man said, 'I will not have this arrow taken out until I know who shot me, what his caste is, what his name is...' He would die before this could be determined.","author":"Majjhima Nikaya","source":"Majjhima Nikaya — Culamalunkya Sutta","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-majjhima-18","text":"As a mother would risk her own life to protect her child, her only child, even so should one cultivate a boundless mind towards all beings.","author":"Majjhima Nikaya","source":"Majjhima Nikaya — Metta Sutta","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-samyutta-19","text":"This arises because that arises. This ceases because that ceases. With the arising of ignorance comes the arising of fabrications.","author":"Samyutta Nikaya","source":"Samyutta Nikaya — Nidana Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-samyutta-20","text":"Form is not self. If form were self, then form would not lead to affliction.","author":"Samyutta Nikaya","source":"Samyutta Nikaya — Khandha Vagga","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-anguttar-21","text":"Monks, I do not see even one other quality, so conducive to great harm as an undeveloped mind. An undeveloped mind conduces to great harm.","author":"Anguttara Nikaya","source":"Anguttara Nikaya — Ones","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-anguttar-22","text":"Monks, I do not see even one other quality so conducive to great benefit as a developed mind. A developed mind conduces to great benefit.","author":"Anguttara Nikaya","source":"Anguttara Nikaya — Ones","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-anguttar-23","text":"Monks, there are two gifts: the gift of material things, and the gift of the Dhamma. Of these two gifts, the gift of the Dhamma is supreme.","author":"Anguttara Nikaya","source":"Anguttara Nikaya — Twos","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-sutta-ni-24","text":"Whatever living beings there may be, without exception, whether they are weak or strong, long or large, medium, short, small or fat, seen or unseen, those who dwell near and those who dwell far, those who are born and those who are yet to be born — may all beings without exception be happy.","author":"Sutta Nipata","source":"Sutta Nipata — Metta Sutta","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-sutta-ni-25","text":"May you be well, may you be happy, may you be free from suffering. This is the wish of one who walks the path of the Dhamma.","author":"Sutta Nipata","source":"Sutta Nipata — Sela Sutta","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-udana-26","text":"There is, monks, an unborn, unbecome, unmade, unfabricated. If there were not that unborn, unbecome, unmade, unfabricated, there would be no escape from the born, become, made, fabricated.","author":"Udana","source":"Udana — Bodhi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-itivutta-27","text":"Monks, there are two extremes that are not to be indulged in by one who has gone forth from the home life. What are the two? That which is devoted to indulgence of pleasure in sensual pleasures, which is low, coarse, the way of the worldling, ignoble, and unbeneficial; and that which is devoted to self-mortification, which is painful, ignoble, and unbeneficial.","author":"Itivuttaka","source":"Itivuttaka — Dukanipata","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-itivutta-28","text":"Avoiding both these extremes, the Tathagata has awakened to the middle way, which gives rise to vision, which gives rise to knowledge, and which leads to calm, to direct knowledge, to enlightenment, to Nibbana.","author":"Itivuttaka","source":"Itivuttaka — Dukanipata","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-digha-ni-29","text":"Therefore, Ananda, be islands unto yourselves, refuges unto yourselves, seeking no external refuge; with the Dhamma as your island, the Dhamma as your refuge, seeking no other refuge.","author":"Digha Nikaya","source":"Digha Nikaya — Mahaparinibbana Sutta","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-digha-ni-30","text":"Impermanent are all compounded things. Work out your salvation with diligence. These were the last words of the Tathagata.","author":"Digha Nikaya","source":"Digha Nikaya — Mahaparinibbana Sutta","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"pali-ext-000031","text":"HISTOIRE DE LA RÉVOLUTION FRANÇAISE.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000032","text":"NOUVEAUX MASSACRES DES PRISONNIERS A VERSAILLES.--ABUS DE POUVOIR ET DILAPIDATIONS DE LA COMMUNE.--ÉLECTION DES DÉPUTÉS A LA CONVENTION.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000033","text":"--COMPOSITION DE LA DÉPUTATION DE PARIS.--POSITION ET PROJETS DES GIRONDINS; CARACTÈRE DES CHEFS DE CE PARTI; DU FÉDÉRALISME.--ÉTAT DU PARTI PARISIEN ET DE LA COMMUNE.--OUVERTURE DE LA CONVENTION NATIONALE LE 20 SEPTEMBRE 1792; ABOLITION DE LA ROYAUTÉ; ÉTABLISSEMENT DE LA RÉPUBLIQUE.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000034","text":"--PREMIÈRE LUTTE DES GIRONDINS ET DES MONTAGNARDS; DÉNONCIATION DE ROBESPIERRE ET DE MARAT.--DÉCLARATION DE L'UNITÉ ET DE L'INDIVISIBILITÉ DE LA RÉPUBLIQUE.--DISTRIBUTION ET FORCES DES PARTIS DANS LA CONVENTION.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000035","text":"--CHANGEMENT DANS LE POUVOIR EXÉCUTIF.--DANTON QUITTE SON MINISTÈRE.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000036","text":"--CRÉATION DE DIVERS COMITÉS ADMINISTRATIFS ET DU COMITÉ DE CONSTITUTION.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000037","text":"Tandis que les armées françaises arrêtaient la marche des coalisés, Paris était toujours dans le trouble et la confusion.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000038","text":"Cependant les commissaires envoyés par la commune avaient été partout repoussés, parce que la France ne partageait pas les fureurs que le danger avait excitées dans la capitale.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000039","text":"Mais dans les environs de Paris, tous les meurtres ne s'étaient pas bornés à ceux dont on a déjà lu le récit.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000040","text":"Il s'était formé dans cette ville une troupe d'assassins que les massacres de septembre avaient familiarisés avec le sang, et qui avaient besoin d'en répandre encore.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000041","text":"Déjà quelques cents hommes étaient partis pour extraire des prisons d'Orléans les accusés de haute trahison.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000042","text":"Ces malheureux, par un dernier décret, devaient être conduits à Saumur.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000043","text":"Cependant leur destination fut changée en route, et ils furent acheminés vers Paris.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000044","text":"Le 9 septembre on apprit qu'ils devaient arriver le 10 à Versailles.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000045","text":"Aussitôt, soit que de nouveaux ordres fussent donnés à la bande des égorgeurs, soit que la nouvelle de cette arrivée suffît pour réveiller leur ardeur sanguinaire, ils envahirent Versailles du 9 au 10.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000046","text":"A l'instant le bruit se répandit que de nouveaux massacres allaient être commis.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000047","text":"Le maire de Versailles prit toutes les précautions pour empêcher de nouveaux malheurs.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000048","text":"Le président du tribunal criminel courut à Paris avertir le ministre Danton du danger qui menaçait les prisonniers; mais il n'obtint qu'une réponse à toutes ses instances: _Ces hommes-là sont bien coupables_.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000049","text":"«Soit, ajouta le président Alquier, mais la loi seule doit en faire justice.--Eh!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000050","text":"ne voyez-vous pas, reprit Danton d'une voix terrible, que je vous aurais déjà répondu d'une autre manière si je le pouvais!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000051","text":"Que vous importent ces prisonniers?","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000052","text":"Retournez à vos fonctions et ne vous occupez plus d'eux...»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000053","text":"Le lendemain, les prisonniers arrivèrent à Versailles.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000054","text":"Là périrent Delessart et d'Abancourt, mis en accusation comme ministres, et Brissac, comme chef de la garde constitutionnelle, licenciée sous la législative.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000055","text":"Immédiatement après cette exécution, les assassins coururent aux prisons de la ville, et renouvelèrent les scènes des premiers jours de septembre, en employant les mêmes moyens, et en parodiant, comme à Paris, les formes judiciaires.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000056","text":"Ce dernier événement, arrivé à cinq jours d'intervalle du premier, acheva de produire une terreur universelle.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000057","text":"A Paris, le comité de surveillance ne ralentit point son action: tandis que les prisons venaient d'être vidées par la mort, il recommença à les remplir en lançant de nouveaux mandats d'arrêt.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000058","text":"Pendant que la commune exerçait sa puissance à Paris, elle envoyait des commissaires dans les départemens pour y justifier sa conduite, y conseiller son exemple, y recommander aux électeurs des députés de son choix, et y décrier ceux qui la contrariaient dans l'assemblée législative.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000059","text":"Tous les effets des malheureux massacrés dans les prisons de Paris et sur la route de Versailles avaient été séquestrés, et déposés dans les vastes salles du comité de surveillance.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000060","text":"Jamais la commune ne voulut représenter ni les objets, ni leur valeur, et refusa même toute réponse à cet égard, soit au ministère de l'intérieur, soit au directoire du département, qui, comme on sait, avait été converti en simple commission de contributions.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000061","text":"Elle fit plus encore, elle se mit à vendre de sa propre autorité le mobilier des grands hôtels, sur lesquels les scellés étaient restés apposés depuis le départ des propriétaires.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000062","text":"Vainement l'administration supérieure lui faisait-elle des défenses: toute la classe des subordonnés chargés de l'exécution des ordres, ou appartenait à la municipalité, ou était trop faible pour agir.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000063","text":"Les ordres ne recevaient ainsi aucune exécution.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000064","text":"La garde nationale, recomposée sous la dénomination de sections armées, et remplie d'hommes de toute espèce, était dans une désorganisation complète.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000065","text":"Tantôt elle se prêtait au mal, tantôt elle le laissait commettre par négligence.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000066","text":"Des postes étaient complètement abandonnés, parce que les hommes de garde, n'étant pas relevés, même après quarante-huit heures, se retiraient épuisés de dégoût et de fatigue.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000067","text":"Tous les citoyens paisibles avaient quitté ce corps, naguère si régulier, si utile; et Santerre, qui le commandait, était trop faible et trop peu intelligent pour le réorganiser.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000068","text":"La sûreté de Paris était donc livrée au hasard, et d'une part la commune, de l'autre la populace, y pouvaient tout entreprendre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000069","text":"Parmi les dépouilles de la royauté, les plus précieuses, et par conséquent les plus convoitées, étaient celles que renfermait le Garde-Meuble, riche dépôt de tous les effets qui servaient autrefois à la splendeur du trône.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000070","text":"Depuis le 10 août, ce dépôt avait éveillé la cupidité de la multitude, et plus d'une circonstance excitait la surveillance de l'inspecteur de l'établissement.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000071","text":"Celui-ci avait fait réquisitions sur réquisitions pour obtenir une garde suffisante; mais soit désordre, soit difficulté de suffire à tous les postes, soit enfin négligence volontaire, on ne lui fournissait point les forces qu'il demandait.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000072","text":"Pendant la nuit du 16 septembre, le Garde-Meuble fut volé, et la plus grande partie de ce qu'il contenait passa dans des mains inconnues, que l'autorité fit depuis d'inutiles efforts pour découvrir.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000073","text":"On attribua ce nouvel événement aux hommes qui avaient secrètement ordonné les massacres.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000074","text":"Cependant ils n'étaient plus excités ici ni par le fanatisme, ni par une politique sanguinaire; et, en leur supposant le motif du vol, ils avaient dans les dépôts de la commune de quoi satisfaire la plus grande ambition.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000075","text":"On a dit, à la vérité, qu'on fit cet enlèvement pour payer la retraite du roi de Prusse, ce qui est absurde, et pour fournir aux dépenses du parti, ce qui est plus vraisemblable, mais ce qui n'est nullement prouvé.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000076","text":"Au reste, le vol du Garde-Meuble doit peu influer sur le jugement qu'il faut porter de la commune et de ses chefs.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000077","text":"Une partie fut impudemment volée par des subalternes, tels que Sergent, surnommé _Agathe_ à cause d'un bijou précieux dont il s'était paré; une autre partie servit aux frais du gouvernement extraordinaire qu'avait institué la commune.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000078","text":"C'était une guerre faite à l'ancienne société, et toute guerre est souillée du meurtre et du pillage.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000079","text":"Telle était la situation de Paris, pendant qu'on faisait les élections pour la convention nationale.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000080","text":"Les députés même, siégeant avec tant de faiblesse dans l'assemblée législative, ajournaient l'énergie à la réunion de cette convention, espérance commune de tous les partis.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000081","text":"On s'agitait pour les élections dans la France entière.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000082","text":"Les clubs exerçaient à cet égard une grande influence.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000083","text":"Les jacobins de Paris avaient fait imprimer et répandre la liste de tous les votes émis pendant la session législative, afin qu'elle servît de documens aux électeurs.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000084","text":"Les députés qui avaient voté contre les lois désirées par le parti populaire, et surtout ceux qui avaient absous Lafayette, étaient particulièrement désignés.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000085","text":"Néanmoins, pour les provinces où les discordes de la capitale n'avaient pas encore pénétré, les girondins, même les plus odieux aux agitateurs de Paris, étaient nommés à cause de leurs talens reconnus.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000086","text":"Presque tous les membres de l'assemblée actuelle étaient réélus.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000087","text":"Beaucoup de constituans, que le décret de non-réélection avait exclus de la première législature, furent appelés à faire partie de cette convention.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000088","text":"Dans le nombre on distinguait Buzot et Pétion.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000089","text":"Parmi les nouveaux membres figuraient naturellement les hommes qui, dans leurs départemens, s'étaient signalés par leur énergie et leur exaltation, ou les écrivains qui, comme Louvet, s'étaient fait connaître, par leurs talens, à la capitale et aux provinces.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000090","text":"A Paris, la faction violente qui avait dominé depuis le 10 août, se rendit maîtresse des élections et mit en avant tous les hommes de son choix.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000091","text":"Robespierre, Danton furent les premiers nommés.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000092","text":"Les jacobins, le conseil de la commune accueillirent cette nouvelle par des applaudissemens.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000093","text":"Après eux furent élus Camille Desmoulins, fameux par ses écrits; David, par ses tableaux; Fabre-d'Églantine, par ses ouvrages comiques et une grande participation aux troubles révolutionnaires; Legendre, Panis, Sergent, Billaud-Varennes, par leur conduite à la commune.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000094","text":"On y ajouta le procureur-syndic Manuel, Robespierre jeune, frère du célèbre Maximilien; Collot-d'Herbois, ancien comédien; le duc d'Orléans, qui avait abdiqué ses titres, et s'appelait Philippe-Égalité.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000095","text":"Il manquait à cette étrange réunion le cynique et sanguinaire Marat.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000096","text":"Cet homme étrange avait, par l'audace de ses écrits, quelque chose de surprenant, même pour des gens qui venaient d'être témoins des journées de septembre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000097","text":"Les députés arrivaient successivement à Paris, et à mesure que leur nombre devenait plus grand, et que les journées qui avaient produit une terreur si profonde s'éloignaient, on commençait à se rassurer, et à se prononcer contre les désordres de la capitale.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000098","text":"La crainte de l'ennemi était diminuée par la contenance de Dumouriez dans l'Argonne: la haine des _aristocrates_ se changeait en pitié, depuis l'horrible sacrifice qu'on en avait fait à Paris et à Versailles.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000099","text":"Ces forfaits, qui avaient trouvé tant d'approbateurs égarés ou tant de censeurs timides, ces forfaits, devenus plus hideux par le vol qui venait de se joindre au meurtre, excitaient la réprobation générale.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000100","text":"Les girondins indignés de tant de crimes, et courroucés de l'oppression personnelle qu'ils avaient subie pendant un mois entier, devenaient plus fermes et plus énergiques.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000101","text":"Brillans de talent et de courage aux yeux de la France, invoquant la justice et l'humanité, ils devaient avoir l'opinion publique pour eux, et déjà ils en menaçaient hautement leurs adversaires.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000102","text":"Cependant, si les girondins étaient également prononcés contre les excès de Paris, ils n'éprouvaient et n'excitaient pas tous ces ressentimens personnels qui enveniment les haines de parti.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000103","text":"Brissot par exemple, en ne cessant aux Jacobins de lutter d'éloquence avec Robespierre, lui avait inspiré une haine profonde.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000104","text":"Avec des lumières, des talens, Brissot produisait beaucoup d'effet; mais il n'avait ni assez de considération personnelle, ni assez d'habileté pour être le chef du parti, et la haine de Robespierre le grandissait en lui imputant ce rôle.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000105","text":"Lorsqu'à la veille de l'insurrection, les girondins écrivirent une lettre à Bose, peintre du roi, le bruit d'un traité se répandit, et on prétendit que Brissot, chargé d'or, allait partir pour Londres.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000106","text":"Il n'en était rien; mais Marat, à qui les bruits les plus insignifians, ou même les mieux démentis, suffisaient pour établir ses accusations, n'en avait pas moins lancé un mandat d'arrêt contre Brissot, lors de l'emprisonnement général des prétendus conspirateurs du 10 août.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000107","text":"Une grande rumeur s'en était suivie, et le mandat d'arrêt ne fut pas exécuté.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000108","text":"Mais les jacobins n'en disaient pas moins que Brissot était vendu à Brunswick; Robespierre le répétait et le croyait, tant sa fausse intelligence était portée à croire coupables ceux qu'il haïssait.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000109","text":"Louvet lui avait inspiré tout autant de haine, en se faisant le second de Brissot aux Jacobins et dans le journal _la Sentinelle_.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000110","text":"Louvet, plein de talent et de hardiesse, s'attaquait directement aux hommes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000111","text":"Ses personnalités virulentes, reproduites chaque jour par la voie d'un journal, en avaient fait l'ennemi le plus dangereux et le plus détesté du parti Robespierre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000112","text":"Le ministre Roland avait déplu à tout le parti jacobin et municipal par sa courageuse lettre du 3 septembre, et par sa résistance aux empiétemens de la commune; mais n'ayant rivalisé avec aucun individu, il n'inspirait qu'une colère d'opinion.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000113","text":"Il n'avait offensé personnellement que Danton, en lui résistant dans le conseil, ce qui était peu dangereux, car de tous les hommes il n'y en avait pas dont le ressentiment fût moins à craindre que celui de Danton.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000114","text":"Déjà ils s'efforçaient de répandre contre Roland un bas ridicule.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000115","text":"Sa femme, disaient-ils, gouvernait pour lui, dirigeait ses amis, les récompensait même de ses faveurs.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000116","text":"Dans son ignoble langage, Marat l'appelait _la Circé_ du parti.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000117","text":"Guadet, Vergniaud, Gensonné, quoiqu'ils eussent répandu un grand éclat dans la législative, et qu'ils se fussent opposés au parti jacobin, n'avaient cependant pas éveillé encore toute la haine qu'ils excitèrent plus tard.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000118","text":"Guadet même avait plu aux républicains énergiques par ses attaques hardies contre Lafayette et la cour.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000119","text":"Guadet, vif, prompt à s'élancer en avant, passait du plus grand emportement au plus grand sang-froid; et, maître de lui à la tribune, il y brillait par l'à-propos et les mouvemens.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000120","text":"Aussi devait-il, comme tous les hommes, aimer un exercice dans lequel il excellait, en abuser même, et prendre trop de plaisir à abattre avec la parole un parti qui lui répondrait bientôt avec la mort.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000121","text":"Vergniaud n'avait pas aussi bien réussi que Guadet auprès des esprits violens, parce qu'il ne montra jamais autant d'ardeur contre la cour, mais il avait été moins exposé aussi à les blesser, parce que, dans son abandon et sa nonchalance, il heurtait moins les personnes que son ami Guadet.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000122","text":"Les passions éveillaient peu ce tribun, le laissaient sommeiller au milieu des agitations de parti, et, ne le portant pas au-devant des hommes, ne l'exposaient guère à leur haine.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000123","text":"Cependant il n'était point indifférent.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000124","text":"Il avait un coeur noble, une belle et lucide intelligence, et le feu oisif de son être, s'y portant par intervalle, l'échauffait, l'élevait jusqu'à la plus sublime énergie.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000125","text":"Il n'avait pas la vivacité des reparties de Guadet, mais il s'animait à la tribune, il y répandait une éloquence abondante, et, grâce à une souplesse d'organe extraordinaire, il rendait ses pensées avec une facilité, une fécondité d'expression, qu'aucun homme n'a égalées.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000126","text":"L'élocution de Mirabeau était, comme son caractère, inégale et forte; celle de Vergniaud, toujours élégante et noble, devenait, avec les circonstances, grande et énergique.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000127","text":"Mais toutes les exhortations de l'épouse de Roland ne réussissaient pas toujours à éveiller cet athlète, souvent dégoûté des hommes, souvent opposé aux imprudences de ses amis, et peu convaincu surtout de l'utilité des paroles contre la force.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000128","text":"Gensonné, plein de sens et de probité, mais doué d'une facilité d'expression médiocre, et capable seulement de faire de bons rapports, avait peu figuré encore à la tribune.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000129","text":"Cependant des passions fortes, un caractère obstiné, devaient lui valoir chez ses amis beaucoup d'influence, et chez ses ennemis la haine, qui atteint le caractère toujours plus que le talent.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000130","text":"Buzot, plein de sens, d'élévation d'âme, de courage, joignant à une belle figure une élocution ferme et simple, imposait aux passions par toute la noblesse de sa personne, et exerçait autour de lui le plus grand ascendant moral.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000131","text":"Barbaroux, élu par ses concitoyens, venait d'arriver du Midi, avec un de ses amis député comme lui à la convention nationale.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000132","text":"C'était un homme peu cultivé, mais hardi, entreprenant, et tout dévoué à Barbaroux.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000133","text":"On se souvient que ce dernier idolâtrait Roland et Pétion, qu'il regardait Marat comme un fou atroce, Robespierre comme un ambitieux, surtout depuis que Panis le lui avait proposé comme un dictateur indispensable.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000134","text":"Révolté des crimes commis depuis son absence, il les imputait volontiers à des hommes qu'il détestait déjà, et il se prononça, dès son arrivée, avec une énergie qui rendait toute réconciliation impossible.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000135","text":"Inférieur à ses amis par l'esprit, mais doué d'intelligence et de facilité, beau, héroïque, il se répandit en menaces, et en quelques jours il obtint autant de haine que ceux qui pendant toute la législative n'avaient cessé de blesser les opinions et les hommes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000136","text":"Le personnage autour duquel se rangeait tout le parti, et qui jouissait d'une considération universelle, était Pétion.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000137","text":"Maire pendant la législative, il avait, par sa lutte avec la cour, acquis une popularité immense.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000138","text":"A la vérité il avait, le 9 août, préféré une délibération à un combat; depuis il s'était prononcé contre septembre, et s'était séparé de la commune, comme Bailly en 1790; mais cette opposition tranquille et silencieuse, sans le brouiller encore avec la faction, le lui avait rendu redoutable.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000139","text":"Plein de lumières, de calme, parlant rarement, ne voulant jamais rivaliser de talent avec personne, il exerçait sur tout le monde, et sur Robespierre lui-même, l'ascendant d'une raison froide, équitable, et universellement respectée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000140","text":"Quoique réputé girondin, tous les partis voulaient son suffrage, tous le redoutaient, et, dans la nouvelle assemblée, il avait pour lui non-seulement le côté droit, mais toute la masse moyenne, et beaucoup même du côté gauche.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000141","text":"Mais à Paris, ils n'étaient pas chez eux, ils se trouvaient au milieu de leurs ennemis, et ils avaient à redouter la violence des classes inférieures, qui s'agitaient au-dessous d'eux, et surtout la violence de l'avenir, qui allait croître avec les passions révolutionnaires.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000142","text":"Le premier reproche qu'on leur adressa fut de vouloir sacrifier Paris.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000143","text":"Déjà on leur avait imputé de vouloir se réfugier dans les départemens et au-delà de la Loire.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000144","text":"Les torts de Paris à leur égard étant plus grands depuis les 2 et 3 septembre, on leur supposa d'autant plus l'intention de l'abandonner, on prétendit qu'ils avaient voulu réunir la convention ailleurs.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000145","text":"Peu à peu les soupçons, s'arrangeant, prirent une forme plus régulière.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000146","text":"On leur reprochait de vouloir rompre l'unité nationale, et composer des quatre-vingt-trois départements, quatre-vingt-trois états, tous égaux entre eux, et unis par un simple lien fédératif.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000147","text":"On ajoutait qu'ils voulaient par-là détruire la suprématie de Paris, et s'assurer une domination personnelle dans leurs départemens respectifs.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000148","text":"C'est alors que fut imaginée la calomnie du fédéralisme.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000149","text":"Et d'ailleurs, entre un gouvernement fédératif et un gouvernement unique et central, toute la différence consistant dans le plus ou moins d'énergie des institutions locales, le crime d'une telle idée était bien vague, s'il existait.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000150","text":"Buzot surtout soutenait souvent cette doctrine, et Brissot, grand admirateur des Américains, la défendait également, plutôt comme opinion philosophique que comme projet applicable à la France.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000151","text":"Ces conversations divulguées donnèrent plus de poids à la calomnie du fédéralisme.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000152","text":"Aux Jacobins, on agita gravement la question du fédéralisme, et on souleva mille fureurs contre les girondins.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000153","text":"On prétendit qu'ils voulaient détruire le faisceau de la puissance révolutionnaire, lui enlever cette unité qui en faisait la force, et cela, pour se faire rois dans leurs provinces.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000154","text":"Les girondins répondirent de leur côté par des reproches plus réels, mais qui malheureusement étaient exagérés aussi, et qui perdaient de leur force en perdant de leur vérité.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000155","text":"Ils reprochaient à la commune de s'être rendue souveraine, d'avoir par ses usurpations empiété sur la souveraineté nationale, et de s'être arrogé à elle seule une puissance qui n'appartenait qu'à la France entière.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000156","text":"Ils lui reprochaient de vouloir dominer la convention, comme elle avait opprimé l'assemblée législative; ils disaient qu'en siégeant auprès d'elle, les mandataires nationaux n'étaient pas en sûreté, et qu'ils siégeraient au milieu des assassins de septembre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000157","text":"Ils l'accusaient d'avoir déshonoré la révolution pendant les quarante jours qui suivirent le 10 août, et de n'avoir rempli la députation de Paris que d'hommes signalés pendant ces horribles saturnales.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000158","text":"Mais ils ajoutaient des reproches aussi vagues que ceux de fédéralisme dont eux-mêmes étaient l'objet.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000159","text":"On les nommait les triumvirs, et cependant il n'y avait guère d'union entre eux.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000160","text":"Mais parmi ces hommes, il n'y avait encore ni un usurpateur, ni des conjurés d'accord entre eux; et il était imprudent de donner à des adversaires, déjà plus forts que soi, l'avantage d'être accusés injustement.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000161","text":"Cependant on essaya de s'entendre avant l'ouverture de la convention nationale, et il y eut diverses réunions dans lesquelles on proposa de s'expliquer franchement, et de terminer des disputes funestes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000162","text":"Danton s'y prêtait de très bonne foi[1], parce qu'il n'y apportait aucun orgueil, et qu'il souhaitait avant tout le succès de la révolution.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000163","text":"Pétion montra beaucoup de froideur et de raison; mais Robespierre fut aigre comme un homme blessé; les girondins furent fiers et sévères comme des hommes innocens, indignés, et qui croient avoir dans les mains leur vengeance assurée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000164","text":"Barbaroux dit qu'il n'y avait aucune alliance possible _entre le crime et la vertu_, et de part et d'autre on se retira plus éloigné d'une réconciliation qu'avant de s'être vu.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000165","text":"Tous les jacobins se rangèrent autour de Robespierre, les girondins et la masse sage et modérée autour de Pétion.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000166","text":"Tel était l'avis des hommes froids; mais d'autres moins calmes firent, comme d'usage, des projets qui, ne pouvant être encore exécutés, avaient le danger d'avertir et d'irriter leurs adversaires.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000167","text":"Ils proposèrent de casser la municipalité, de déplacer au besoin la convention, de transporter son siège ailleurs qu'à Paris, de la former en cour de justice, pour juger sans appel les conspirateurs, de lui composer enfin une garde particulière prise dans les quatre-vingt-trois départemens.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000168","text":"Ces projets n'eurent aucune suite et ne servirent qu'à irriter les passions.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000169","text":"Les girondins s'en reposèrent sur la conscience publique, qui, suivant eux, allait se soulever aux accens de leur éloquence et au récit des crimes qu'ils devaient dénoncer.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000170","text":"Ils se donnèrent rendez-vous à la tribune de la convention pour y écraser leurs adversaires.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000171","text":"[Note 1: Voyez Durand-Maillanne, Dumouriez, Meillan, et tous les contemporains.]","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000172","text":"Enfin, le 20 septembre, les députés à la convention se réunirent aux Tuileries pour constituer la nouvelle assemblée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000173","text":"Leur nombre étant suffisant, ils se constituèrent provisoirement, vérifièrent leurs pouvoirs, et procédèrent de suite à la nomination du bureau.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000174","text":"Pétion fut presque à l'unanimité proclamé président.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000175","text":"Brissot, Condorcet, Rabaud Saint-Étienne, Lasource, Vergniaud et Camus, furent élus secrétaires.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000176","text":"Ces choix prouvent quelle était alors dans rassemblée l'influence du parti girondin.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000177","text":"L'assemblée législative, qui depuis le 10 août avait été en permanence, fut informée, le 21, par une députation, que la convention nationale était formée, et que la législature était terminée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000178","text":"Les deux assemblées n'eurent qu'à se confondre l'une dans l'autre, et la convention alla occuper la salle de la législative.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000179","text":"Chabot dit que les représentans du peuple doivent s'assimiler aux citoyens des rangs desquels ils sortent, aux sans-culottes, qui forment la majorité de la nation.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000180","text":"Tallien ajoute qu'on ira chercher le président de la convention à un cinquième étage, et que c'est là que logent le génie et la vertu.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000181","text":"La proposition de Manuel est donc rejetée, et les ennemis de la Gironde prétendent qu'elle a voulu décerner à son chef Pétion les honneurs souverains.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000182","text":"Après cette proposition, une foule d'autres se succèdent sans interruption.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000183","text":"De toutes parts on veut constater par des déclarations authentiques les sentimens qui animent l'assemblée et la France.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000184","text":"On demande que la nouvelle constitution ait pour base l'égalité absolue, que la souveraineté du peuple soit décrétée, que haine soit jurée à la royauté, à la dictature, au triumvirat, à toute autorité individuelle, et que la peine de mort soit décrétée contre quiconque en proposerait une pareille.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000185","text":"Danton met fin à toutes les motions, en faisant décréter que la nouvelle constitution ne sera valable qu'après avoir été sanctionnée par le peuple.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000186","text":"On ajoute que les lois existantes continueront provisoirement d'avoir leur effet, que les autorités non remplacées seront provisoirement maintenues, et que les impôts seront perçus comme par le passé, en attendant les nouveaux systèmes de contribution.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000187","text":"Après ces propositions et ces décrets, Manuel, Collot-d'Herbois, Grégoire, entreprennent la question de la royauté, et demandent que son abolition soit prononcée sur-le-champ.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000188","text":"Le peuple, disent-ils, vient d'être déclaré souverain, mais il ne le sera réellement que lorsque vous l'aurez délivré d'une autorité rivale, celle des rois.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000189","text":"L'assemblée, les tribunes se lèvent pour exprimer une réprobation unanime contre la royauté.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000190","text":"Cependant Bazire voudrait, dit-il, une discussion solennelle sur une question aussi importante, «Qu'est-il besoin de discuter, reprend Grégoire, lorsque tout le monde est d'accord?","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000191","text":"Les cours sont l'atelier du crime, le foyer de la corruption, l'histoire des rois est le martyrologe des nations.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000192","text":"Dès que nous sommes tous également pénétrés de ces vérités, qu'est-il besoin de discuter?»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000193","text":"La discussion est en effet fermée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000194","text":"Il se fait un profond silence, et, sur la déclaration unanime de l'assemblée, le président déclare que la royauté est abolie en France.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000195","text":"Ce décret est accueilli par des applaudissemens universels; la publication en est ordonnée sur-le-champ, ainsi que l'envoi aux armées et à toutes les municipalités.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000196","text":"Lorsque cette institution de la république fut proclamée, les Prussiens menaçaient encore le territoire.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000197","text":"Dumouriez, comme on l'a vu, s'était porté à Sainte-Menehould, et la canonnade du 21, si heureuse pour nos armes, n'était pas encore connue à Paris.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000198","text":"Le lendemain 22, Billaud-Varennes proposa de dater, non plus de l'an 4 de la liberté, mais de l'an 1er de la république.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000199","text":"Cette proposition fut adoptée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000200","text":"L'année 1789 ne fut plus considérée comme ayant commencé la liberté, et la nouvelle ère républicaine s'ouvrit ce jour même, 22 septembre 1792.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000201","text":"Le soir on apprit la canonnade de Valmy, et la joie commença à se répandre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000202","text":"Sur la demande des citoyens d'Orléans, qui se plaignaient de leurs magistrats, il fut décrété que tous les membres des corps administratifs et des tribunaux seraient réélus, et que les conditions d'éligibilité, fixées par la constitution de 91, seraient considérées comme nulles.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000203","text":"Il n'était plus nécessaire de prendre les juges parmi les légistes, ni les administrateurs dans une certaine classe de propriétaires.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000204","text":"Déjà l'assemblée législative avait aboli le marc d'argent, et attribué à tous les citoyens en âge de majorité la capacité électorale.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000205","text":"La convention acheva d'effacer les dernières démarcations, en appelant tous les citoyens à toutes les fonctions les plus diverses.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000206","text":"Ainsi fut commencé le système de l'égalité absolue.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000207","text":"Le 23, tous les ministres furent entendus.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000208","text":"Le député Gambon fit un rapport sur l'état des finances.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000209","text":"Les précédentes assemblées avaient décrété la fabrication de deux milliards sept cents millions d'assignats; deux milliards cinq cents millions avaient été dépensés; restait deux cents millions, dont cent soixante-seize étaient encore à fabriquer, et dont vingt-quatre se trouvaient en caisse.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000210","text":"Les impôts étaient retenus par les départemens pour les achats de grains ordonnés par la dernière assemblée; il fallait de nouvelles ressources extraordinaires.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000211","text":"La masse des biens nationaux s'augmentant tous les jours par l'émigration, on ne craignait pas d'émettre le papier qui les représentait, et on n'hésita pas à le faire: une nouvelle création d'assignats fut donc ordonnée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000212","text":"Roland fut entendu sur l'état de la France et de la capitale.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000213","text":"Aussi sévère et plus hardi encore qu'au 3 septembre, il exposa avec énergie les désordres de Paris, les causes et les moyens de les prévenir.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000214","text":"Il recommanda l'institution prompte d'un gouvernement fort et vigoureux, comme la seule garantie d'ordre dans les états libres.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000215","text":"Son rapport, entendu avec faveur, fut couvert d'applaudissemens, et n'excita cependant aucune explosion chez ceux qui se regardaient comme accusés dès qu'il s'agissait des troubles de Paris.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000216","text":"Mais à peine ce premier coup d'oeil était-il jeté sur la situation de la France, qu'on apprend la nouvelle de la propagation du désordre dans certains départemens.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000217","text":"Roland écrit une lettre à la convention pour lui dénoncer de nouveaux excès, et en demander la répression.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000218","text":"Aussitôt cette lecture achevée, les députés Kersaint, Buzot, s'élancent à la tribune pour dénoncer les violences de tout genre qui commencent à se commettre partout.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000219","text":"«Les assassinats, disent-ils, sont imités dans les départemens.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000220","text":"Ce n'est pas l'anarchie qu'il faut en accuser, mais des tyrans d'une nouvelle espèce, qui s'élèvent sur la France à peine affranchie.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000221","text":"C'est de Paris que partent tous les jours ces funestes inspirations du crime.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000222","text":"Sur tous les murs de la capitale, on lit des affiches qui provoquent aux meurtres, aux incendies, aux pillages, et des listes de proscription où sont désignées chaque jour de nouvelles victimes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000223","text":"Comment préserver le peuple d'une affreuse misère, si tant de citoyens sont condamnés à cacher leur existence?","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000224","text":"Comment faire espérer à la France une constitution, si la convention, qui doit la décréter, délibère sous les poignards?","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000225","text":"Il faut, pour l'honneur de la révolution, arrêter tant d'excès, et distinguer entre la bravoure civique qui a bravé le despotisme au 10 août, et la cruauté servant, aux 2 et 3 septembre, une tyrannie muette et cachée.»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000226","text":"En conséquence, les orateurs demandent l'établissement d'un comité chargé,","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000227","text":"1. De rendre compte de l'état de la république et de Paris en particulier;","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000228","text":"2. De présenter un projet de loi contre les provocateurs au meurtre et à l'assassinat;","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000229","text":"3. De rendre compte des moyens de donner à la convention nationale une force publique à sa disposition, prise dans les quatre-vingt-trois départemens.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000230","text":"A cette proposition, tous les membres du côté gauche, où s'étaient rangés les esprits les plus ardens de la nouvelle assemblée, poussent des cris tumultueux.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000231","text":"On exagère, suivant eux, les maux de la France.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000232","text":"Les plaintes hypocrites qu'on vient d'entendre partent du fond des cachots, où ont été justement plongés les suspects qui, depuis trois ans, appelaient la guerre civile sur leur patrie.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000233","text":"Les maux dont on se plaint étaient inévitables; le peuple est en état de révolution, et il devait prendre des mesures énergiques pour son salut.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000234","text":"Aujourd'hui, ces momens critiques sont passés, et les déclarations que vient de faire la convention suffiront pour apaiser les troubles.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000235","text":"D'ailleurs, pourquoi une juridiction Extraordinaire?","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000236","text":"Les anciennes lois existent, et suffisent pour les provocations au meurtre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000237","text":"Serait-ce encore une nouvelle loi martiale qu'on voudrait établir?","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000238","text":"Par une contradiction bien ordinaire chez les partis, ceux qui avaient demandé la juridiction extraordinaire du 17 août, ceux qui allaient demander le tribunal révolutionnaire, s'élevaient contre une loi qui, disaient-ils, était une loi de sang!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000239","text":"«Une loi de sang, répond Kersaint, lorsque je veux au contraire en prévenir l'effusion!» Cependant l'ajournement est vivement demandé.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000240","text":"«Ajourner la répression des meurtres, s'écrie Vergniaud, c'est les ordonner!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000241","text":"Les ennemis de la France sont en armes sur notre territoire, et l'on veut que les citoyens français, au lieu de combattre, s'entr'égorgent comme les soldats de Cadmus!...»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000242","text":"Enfin la proposition de Kersaint et Buzot est adoptée tout entière. On décrète qu'il sera préparé des lois pour la punition des provocateurs au meurtre, et pour l'organisation d'une garde départementale.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000243","text":"Cette séance du 24 septembre avait causé une grande émotion dans les esprits; cependant aucun nom n'avait été prononcé, et les accusations étaient restées générales.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000244","text":"Le lendemain, on s'aborde avec les ressentimens de la veille, et d'une part on murmure contre les décrets rendus, de l'autre on éprouve le regret de n'avoir pas assez dit contre la façon appelée _désorganisatrice_.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000245","text":"Tandis qu'on attaque les décrets, ou qu'on les défend, Merlin, autrefois huissier et officier municipal à Thionville, puis député à la législative, où il se signala parmi les patriotes les plus prononcés, Merlin, fameux par son ardeur et sa bravoure, demande la parole.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000246","text":"«Ce sont ceux qui ont provoqué le meurtre et le pillage, qui ont lancé des mandats d'arrêt contre des membres de la législative, qui désignent aux poignards les membres courageux de la convention, et qui imputent au peuple les excès qu'ils ordonnent eux-mêmes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000247","text":"Lorsqu'il en sera temps, il arrachera le voile qu'il ne fait que soulever, dût-il périr sous leurs coups.»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000248","text":"Cependant les triumvirs n'étaient pas nommés.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000249","text":"«Que chacun, ajoute-t-il, me suive à la tribune, et y fasse la même déclaration:--Oui, s'écrie Rebecqui, le courageux ami de Barbaroux; oui, ce parti accusé de projets tyranniques existe, et je le nomme: c'est le parti Robespierre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000250","text":"Marseille le connaît, et nous envoie ici pour le combattre.»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000251","text":"Cette apostrophe hardie cause une grande rumeur dans l'assemblée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000252","text":"Les yeux se dirigent sur Robespierre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000253","text":"Danton se hâte de prendre la parole pour apaiser ces divisions, et écarter des accusations qu'il savait en partie dirigées contre lui-même.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000254","text":"«Ce sera, dit-il, un beau jour pour la république que celui où une explication franche et fraternelle calmera toutes ces défiances.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000255","text":"On parle de dictateurs, de triumvirs; mais cette accusation est vague et doit être signée.--Moi je la signerai, s'écrie de nouveau Rebecqui, en s'élançant au bureau.--Soit, répond Danton; s'il est des coupables, qu'ils soient immolés, fussent-ils les meilleurs de mes amis.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000256","text":"Dans les sociétés patriotiques, au 10 août, au conseil exécutif, j'ai servi la cause de la liberté sans aucune vue personnelle, et avec _l'énergie de mon tempérament_.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000257","text":"Je ne crains donc pas les accusations pour moi-même; mais je veux les épargner à tout le monde.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000258","text":"Il est, j'en conviens, dans la députation de Paris, un homme qu'on pourrait appeler le _Royou_ des républicains: c'est Marat.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000259","text":"Souvent on m'a accusé d'être l'instigateur de ses placards; mais j'invoque le témoignage du président, et je lui demande de déclarer si, dans la commune et les comités, il ne m'a pas vu souvent aux prises avec Marat.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000260","text":"Au reste, cet écrivain tant accusé a passé une partie de sa vie dans les souterrains et les cachots.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000261","text":"La souffrance a altéré son humeur, il faut excuser ses emportemens.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000262","text":"Mais laissez là des discussions tout individuelles, et tâchez de les faire servir à la chose publique.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000263","text":"Portez la peine de mort contre quiconque proposera la dictature ou le triumvirat.» Cette motion est couverte d'applaudissemens.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000264","text":"«Ce n'est pas tout, reprend Danton, il est une autre crainte répandue dans le public, et il faut la dissiper.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000265","text":"On prétend qu'une partie des députés médite le régime fédératif, et la division de la France en une foule de sections.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000266","text":"Il nous importe de former un tout.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000267","text":"Déclarez donc, par un autre décret, l'unité de la France et de son gouvernement.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000268","text":"Ces bases posées, écartons nos défiances, soyons unis, et marchons à notre but!»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000269","text":"Robespierre, personnellement accusé, demande à son tour la parole.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000270","text":"D'abord il annonce que ce n'est pas lui qu'il va défendre, mais la chose publique, attaquée dans sa personne.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000271","text":"S'adressant à Rebecqui: «Citoyen, lui dit-il, qui n'avez pas craint de m'accuser, je vous remercie.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000272","text":"Je reconnais à votre courage la cité célèbre qui vous a député.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000273","text":"La patrie, vous et moi, nous gagnerons tous à cette accusation.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000274","text":"«On désigne, continue-t-il, un parti qui médite une nouvelle tyrannie, et c'est moi qu'on en nomme le chef.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000275","text":"L'accusation est vague; mais, grâce à tout ce que j'ai fait pour la liberté, il me sera facile d'y répondre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000276","text":"En disant ces mots, il montrait le côté droit de la Convention.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000277","text":"Osselin lui-même, fatigué de cette énumération, interrompt Robespierre, et lui demande de donner une explication franche.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000278","text":"«Il ne s'agit pas de ce que tu as fait, dit Lecointe-Puiravaux, mais de ce qu'on t'accuse de faire aujourd'hui.» Robespierre se replie alors sur la liberté des opinions, sur le droit sacré de la défense, sur la chose publique, aussi compromise que lui-même dans cette accusation.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000279","text":"On l'invite encore à être plus bref, mais il continue avec la même diffusion.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000280","text":"Rappelant les fameux décrets qu'il a fait rendre contre la réélection des constituans et contre la nomination des députés à des places données par le gouvernement, il demande si ce sont là des preuves d'ambition.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000281","text":"Récriminant ensuite contre ses adversaires, il renouvelle l'accusation de fédéralisme, et finit en demandant l'adoption des décrets proposés par Danton, et un examen sérieux de l'accusation intentée contre lui.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000282","text":"Déjà nous avons rapporté ces faits, et on a pu juger si ces vagues et insignifians propos des amis de Robespierre pouvaient servir de base à une accusation.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000283","text":"Barbaroux reprend une à une les imputations adressées aux girondins; il demande qu'on proscrive le fédéralisme par un décret; que tous les membres de la convention nationale jurent de se laisser bloquer dans la capitale, et d'y mourir plutôt que de la quitter.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000284","text":"«Pour Robespierre, ajoute Barbaroux, j'éprouve un vif regret de l'avoir accusé, car je l'aimais, je l'estimais autrefois.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000285","text":"Oui, nous l'aimions, et nous l'estimions tous, et cependant nous l'avons accusé!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000286","text":"Mais qu'il reconnaisse ses torts, et nous nous désistons.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000287","text":"Qu'il cesse de se plaindre, car s'il a sauvé la liberté par ses écrits, nous l'avons défendue de nos personnes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000288","text":"Citoyens, quand le jour du péril sera arrivé, alors on nous jugera, alors nous verrons si les faiseurs de placards sauront mourir avec nous!» De nombreux applaudissemens accompagnent Barbaroux jusqu'à sa place.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000289","text":"Au mot de placards, Marat réclame la parole.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000290","text":"Cambon la demande après lui, et obtient la préférence.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000291","text":"Il dénonce alors des placards où la dictature est proposée comme indispensable, et qui sont signés du nom de Marat.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000292","text":"A ces mots, chacun s'éloigne de celui-ci, et il répond par un sourire aux mépris qu'on lui témoigne.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000293","text":"A Cambon succèdent d'autres accusateurs de Marat et de la commune.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000294","text":"Marat fait de longs efforts pour obtenir la parole; mais Panis l'obtient encore avant lui, pour répondre aux allégations de Barbaroux.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000295","text":"Panis nie maladroitement des faits vrais, mais peu probans, et qu'il valait mieux avouer, en se repliant sur leur peu de valeur.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000296","text":"Il est alors interrompu par Brissot, qui lui demande raison du mandat d'arrêt lancé contre sa personne.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000297","text":"Après ces longues explications, à tout moment interrompues et reprises, Marat, insistant toujours pour avoir la parole, l'obtient enfin, lorsqu'il n'est plus possible de la lui refuser.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000298","text":"C'était la première fois qu'il paraissait à la tribune.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000299","text":"Son aspect produit un mouvement d'indignation, et un bruit affreux s'élève contre lui.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000300","text":"Négligemment vêtu, portant une casquette, qu'il dépose sur la tribune, et promenant sur son auditoire un sourire convulsif et méprisant: «J'ai, dit-il, un grand nombre d'ennemis personnels dans cette assemblée...","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000301","text":"s'écrient la plupart des députés.--J'ai dans cette assemblée, reprend Marat avec la même assurance, un grand nombre d'ennemis personnels, je les rappelle à la pudeur.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000302","text":"Qu'ils s'épargnent les clameurs furibondes contre un homme qui a servi la liberté, et eux-mêmes, plus qu'ils ne pensent.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000303","text":"«On parle de triumvirat, de dictature, on en attribue le projet à la députation de Paris; eh bien!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000304","text":"je dois à la justice de déclarer que mes collègues, et notamment Robespierre et Danton, s'y sont toujours opposés, et que j'ai toujours eu à les combattre sur ce point.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000305","text":"Moi le premier, et le seul en France, entre tous les écrivains politiques, j'ai songé à cette mesure, comme au seul moyen d'écraser les traîtres et les conspirateurs.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000306","text":"C'est moi seul qu'il faut punir; mais avant de punir il faut entendre.» Ici quelques applaudissemens éclatent, mais peu nombreux.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000307","text":"Marat reprend: «Au milieu des machinations éternelles d'un roi perfide, d'une cour abominable, et des faux patriotes qui, dans les deux assemblées, vendaient la liberté publique, me reprocherez-vous d'avoir imaginé le seul moyen de salut, et d'avoir appelé la vengeance sur les têtes criminelles?","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000308","text":"non, car le peuple vous désavouerait.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000309","text":"Il a senti qu'il ne lui restait plus que ce moyen, et c'est en se faisant dictateur lui-même qu'il s'est délivré des traîtres.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000310","text":"«J'ai frémi plus qu'un autre à l'idée de ces mouvemens terribles, et c'est pour qu'ils ne fussent pas éternellement vains que j'aurais désiré qu'ils fussent dirigés par une main juste et ferme!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000311","text":"Si, à la prise de la Bastille, on eût compris la nécessité de cette mesure, cinq cents têtes scélérates seraient tombées à ma voix; et la paix eût été affermie dès cette époque.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000312","text":"Mais faute d'avoir employé cette énergie aussi sage que nécessaire, cent mille patriotes ont été égorgés, et cent mille sont menacés de l'être!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000313","text":"Mes idées, quelque révoltantes qu'elles vous parussent, ne tendaient qu'au bonheur public.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000314","text":"Si vous n'étiez point vous-mêmes à la hauteur de m'entendre, tant pis pour vous!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000315","text":"Le profond silence qui avait régné jusque-là est interrompu par quelques éclats de rire, qui ne déconcertent point l'orateur, beaucoup plus effrayant que risible.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000316","text":"Il continue: «Telle était mon opinion, écrite, signée, publiquement soutenue.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000317","text":"Si elle était fausse, il fallait la combattre, m'éclairer, et ne point me dénoncer au despotisme.»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000318","text":"«On m'a accusé d'ambition! mais voyez, et jugez-moi. Si j'avais seulement voulu mettre un prix à mon silence, je serais gorgé d'or, et je suis pauvre! Poursuivi sans cesse, j'ai erré de souterrains en souterrains, et j'ai prêché la vérité sur le billot!»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000319","text":"«Pour vous, ouvrez les yeux; loin de consumer votre temps en discussions scandaleuses, perfectionnez la déclaration des droits, établissez la constitution, et posez les bases du gouvernement juste et libre, qui est le véritable objet de vos travaux.»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000320","text":"Une attention universelle avait été accordée à cet homme étrange, et l'assemblée, stupéfaite d'un système aussi effrayant et aussi calculé, avait gardé le silence.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000321","text":"Quelques partisans de Marat, enhardis par ce silence, avaient applaudi; mais ils n'avaient pas été imités, et Marat avait repris sa place sans recevoir ni applaudissemens, ni marques de colère.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000322","text":"Vergniaud, le plus pur, le plus sage des girondins, croit devoir prendre la parole pour réveiller l'indignation de l'assemblée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000323","text":"Il déplore le malheur d'avoir à répondre à un homme chargé de décrets!...","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000324","text":"Chabot, Tallien, se récrient à ces mots, et demandent si ce sont les décrets lancés par le Châtelet pour avoir dévoilé Lafayette.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000325","text":"Vergniaud insiste, et déplore d'avoir à répondre à un homme qui n'a pas purgé les décrets dont il est chargé, à un homme tout dégouttant de calomnies, de fiel et de sang!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000326","text":"Les murmures se renouvellent; mais il continue avec fermeté, et après avoir distingué, dans la députation de Paris, David, Dusaulx et quelques autres membres, il prend en mains la fameuse circulaire de la commune que nous avons déjà citée, et la lit tout entière.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000327","text":"Cependant comme elle était déjà connue, elle ne produit pas autant d'effet qu'une autre pièce, dont le député Boileau fait à son tour la lecture.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000328","text":"C'est une feuille imprimée par Marat, le jour même, et dans laquelle il dit: «Une seule réflexion m'accable, c'est que tous mes efforts pour sauver le peuple n'aboutiront à rien sans une nouvelle insurrection.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000329","text":"A voir la trempe de la plupart des députés à la convention nationale, je désespère du salut public.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000330","text":"Si dans les huit premières séances les bases de la constitution ne sont pas posées, n'attendez plus rien de cette assemblée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000331","text":"Cinquante ans d'anarchie vous attendent, et vous n'en sortirez que par un dictateur, vrai patriote et homme d'état...","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000332","text":"La lecture de cette pièce est souvent interrompue par des cris d'indignation.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000333","text":"A peine est-elle achevée, qu'une foule de membres se déchaînent contre Marat.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000334","text":"Les uns le menacent et crient: A l'Abbaye!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000335","text":"D'autres l'accablent de paroles de mépris.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000336","text":"Il ne répond que par un nouveau sourire à toutes les attaques dont il est l'objet.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000337","text":"Boileau demande un décret d'accusation, et la plus grande partie de l'assemblée veut aller aux voix.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000338","text":"Marat insiste avec sang-froid pour être entendu.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000339","text":"On ne veut l'écouter qu'à la barre; enfin il obtient la tribune.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000340","text":"Selon son expression accoutumée, _il rappelle ses ennemis à la pudeur_.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000341","text":"Quant aux décrets qu'on n'a pas rougi de lui opposer, il s'en fait gloire, parce qu'ils sont le prix de son courage.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000342","text":"D'ailleurs le peuple, en l'envoyant dans cette assemblée nationale, a purgé les décrets, et décidé entre ses accusateurs et lui.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000343","text":"Quant à l'écrit dont on vient dé faire la lecture, il ne le désavouera pas, car le mensonge, dit il, n'approcha jamais de ses lèvres, et la crainte est étrangère à son coeur.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000344","text":"On consent en effet à lire l'article, et l'assemblée apaisée par les expressions modérées de Marat, dans cet article intitulé _Sa nouvelle marche_, le traite avec moins de rigueur; il obtient même quelques marques de satisfaction.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000345","text":"Mais il remonte à la tribune avec son audace ordinaire, et prétend donner une leçon à ses collègues sur le danger de l'emportement et de la prévention.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000346","text":"Si son journal n'avait pas paru le jour même, pour le disculper, on l'envoyait aveuglément dans les fers.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000347","text":"«Mais, dit-il, en montrant un pistolet qu'il portait toujours dans sa poche, et qu'il s'applique sur le front, j'avais de quoi rester libre, et si vous m'aviez décrété d'accusation, je me brûlais la cervelle à cette tribune même.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000348","text":"Voilà le fruit de mes travaux, de mes dangers, de mes souffrances!","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000349","text":"Eh bien, je resterai parmi vous, pour braver vos fureurs!» A ce dernier mot de Marat, ses collègues, rendus à leur indignation, s'écrient que c'est un fou, un scélérat, et se livrent à un long tumulte.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000350","text":"La discussion avait duré plusieurs heures, et cependant qu'avait-on appris?...","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000351","text":"rien sur le projet prétendu d'une dictature au profit d'un triumvirat, mais beaucoup sur le caractère des partis, et sur leur force respective.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000352","text":"On s'accorda avec les girondins pour proscrire septembre et ses horreurs; on leur décerna l'estime due à leurs talens et à leur probité; mais on trouva leurs accusations exagérées et imprudentes, et on ne put s'empêcher de voir dans leur indignation quelques sentimens personnels.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000353","text":"Dès ce moment l'assemblée se distribua en côté droit et côté gauche, comme dans les premiers jours de la constituante.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000354","text":"Au côté droit se placèrent tous les girondins, et ceux qui, sans, être aussi personnellement liés à leur sort, partageaient cependant leur indignation généreuse.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000355","text":"Au centre s'accumulèrent, en nombre considérable, tous les députés honnêtes, mais paisibles, qui, n'étant portés ni par leur caractère, ni par leur talent, à prendre part à la lutte des partis autrement que par leur vote, cherchaient, en se confondant dans la multitude, l'obscurité et la sécurité.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000356","text":"Leur grand nombre dans l'assemblée, le respect encore très grand qu'on avait pour elle, l'empressement que le parti jacobin et municipal mettait à se justifier à ses yeux, tout les rassurait.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000357","text":"Ils aimaient à croire que l'autorité de la convention suffirait, avec le temps, pour dompter les agitateurs; ils n'étaient pas fâchés d'ajourner l'énergie, et de pouvoir dire aux girondins que leurs accusations étaient hasardées.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000358","text":"Ils ne se montraient encore que raisonnables et impartiaux, parfois un peu jaloux de l'éloquence trop fréquente et trop brillante du côté droit; mais bientôt, en présence de la tyrannie, ils allaient devenir faibles et lâches.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000359","text":"On les nomma _la Plaine_, et par opposition on appela _Montagne_ le côté gauche, où tous les jacobins s'étaient amoncelés les uns au-dessus des autres.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000360","text":"Sur les degrés de cette Montagne, on voyait les députés de Paris et ceux des départemens qui devaient leur nomination à la correspondance des clubs, ou qui avaient été gagnés, depuis leur arrivée, par l'idée qu'il ne fallait faire aucun quartier aux ennemis de la révolution.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000361","text":"On y comptait aussi quelques esprits distingués, mais exacts, rigoureux, positifs, auxquels les théories et la philanthropie des girondins déplaisaient comme de vaines abstractions.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000362","text":"Cependant les montagnards étaient peu nombreux encore.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000363","text":"La Plaine, unie au côté droit, composait une majorité immense, qui avait donné la présidence à Pétion, et qui approuvait les attaques des girondins contre septembre, sauf les personnalités, qui semblaient trop précoces et trop peu fondées [1].","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000364","text":"[Note 1: Voyez un extrait des _Mémoires de Garat_ à la fin du volume.]","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000365","text":"C'est surtout contre ces deux derniers projets que les montagnards étaient le plus soulevés.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000366","text":"Ils demandaient si on voulait renouveler la loi martiale et les massacres du Champ-de-Mars, si la convention voulait se faire des satellites et des gardes-du-corps, comme le dernier roi.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000367","text":"Ils renouvelaient ainsi, comme le disaient les girondins, toutes les raisons données par la cour contre le camp sous Paris.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000368","text":"Beaucoup des membres du côté gauche, et même les plus ardens, étaient, en leur qualité de membres de la convention, très prononcés contre les usurpations de la commune; et, à part les députés de Paris, aucun ne la défendait lorsqu'elle était attaquée, ce qui avait lieu tous les jours.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000369","text":"Aussi les décrets se succédèrent-ils vivement.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000370","text":"Comme la commune tardait à se renouveler, en exécution du décret qui prescrivait la réélection de tous les corps administratifs, on ordonna au conseil exécutif de veiller à son renouvellement, et d'en rendre compte à l'assemblée sous trois jours.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000371","text":"Une commission de six membres fut nommée pour recevoir la déclaration, signée de tous ceux qui avaient déposé des effets à l'Hôtel-de-Ville, et pour rechercher l'existence de ces effets, ou vérifier l'emploi qu'en avait fait la municipalité.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000372","text":"Le directoire du département, que la commune insurrectionnelle avait réduit au titre et aux fonctions de simple commission administrative, fut réintégré dans toutes ses attributions, et reprit son titre de directoire.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000373","text":"Les élections communales pour la nomination du maire, de la municipalité, et du conseil général, que les jacobins avaient récemment imaginé de faire à haute voix, pour intimider les faibles, furent de nouveau rendues secrètes par une confirmation de la loi existante.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000374","text":"Les élections déjà opérées d'après ce mode illégal, furent annulées, et les sections se soumirent à les recommencer dans la forme prescrite.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000375","text":"On décréta enfin que tous les prisonniers enfermés sans mandat d'arrêt, seraient élargis sur-le-champ.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000376","text":"C'était là un grand coup porté au comité de surveillance, acharné surtout contre les personnes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000377","text":"Tous ces décrets avaient été rendus dans les premiers jours d'octobre, et la commune, vivement poussée, se voyait obligée à plier sous l'ascendant de la convention.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000378","text":"Cependant le comité de surveillance n'avait pas voulu se laisser battre sans résistance.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000379","text":"Ses membres s'étaient présentés à l'assemblée, disant qu'ils venaient confondre leurs ennemis.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000380","text":"Dépositaires des papiers trouvés chez Laporte, intendant de la liste civile, et condamné, comme on s'en souvient, par le tribunal du 17 août, ils avaient découvert, disaient-ils, une lettre où il était parlé de ce qu'avaient coûté certains décrets, rendus dans les précédentes assemblées.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000381","text":"Ils venaient démasquer les députés vendus à la cour, et prouver la fausseté de leur patriotisme.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000382","text":"s'était écriée l'assemblée avec indignation.--Nous ne pouvons les désigner encore, avaient répondu les membres du comité.»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000383","text":"Sur-le-champ, pour repousser la calomnie, il fut nommé une commission de vingt-quatre députés, étrangers à la constituante et à la législative, chargés de vérifier ces papiers et d'en faire leur rapport.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000384","text":"Marat, inventeur de cette ressource, publia dans son journal qu'il avait rendu aux _Rolandistes_, accusateurs de la commune, la _monnaie de leur pièce_; et il annonça la prétendue découverte d'une trahison des girondins.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000385","text":"Cependant les papiers examinés, aucun des députés actuels ne se trouva compromis, et le comité de surveillance fut déclaré calomniateur.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000386","text":"Les papiers étant trop volumineux pour que les vingt-quatre députés en continuassent l'examen à l'Hôtel-de-Ville, on les transporta dans l'un des comités de l'assemblée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000387","text":"Marat, se voyant ainsi privé de riches matériaux pour ses accusations journalières, s'en irrita beaucoup, et prétendit, dans son journal, qu'on avait voulu détruire la preuve de toutes les trahisons.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000388","text":"Après avoir ainsi réprimé les débordemens de la commune, l'assemblée s'occupa du pouvoir exécutif, et décida que les ministres ne pourraient plus être pris dans son sein.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000389","text":"Danton, obligé d'opter entre les fonctions de ministre de la justice et de membre de la convention, préféra, comme Mirabeau, celles qui lui assuraient la tribune, et quitta le ministère sans rendre compte des dépenses secrètes, disant qu'il avait rendu ce compte au conseil.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000390","text":"Ce fait n'était pas très-exact; mais on n'y regarda pas de plus près, et on passa outre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000391","text":"Sur le refus de François de Neuchâteau, Garat, écrivain distingué, idéologue spirituel, et devenu fameux par l'excellente rédaction du _Journal de Paris_, occupa la place de ministre de la justice.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000392","text":"Servan, fatigué d'une administration laborieuse, et au-dessus non de ses facultés, mais de ses forces, préféra le commandement de l'armée d'observation qu'on formait le long des Pyrénées.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000393","text":"Le ministre Lebrun fut provisoirement chargé d'ajouter le portefeuille de la guerre à celui des affaires étrangères.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000394","text":"Roland enfin offrit aussi sa démission, fatigué qu'il était d'une anarchie si contraire à sa probité et à son inflexible amour de l'ordre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000395","text":"Les girondins proposèrent à l'assemblée de l'inviter à garder le portefeuille.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000396","text":"Les montagnards, et particulièrement Danton, qu'il avait beaucoup contrarié, s'opposèrent à cette démarche comme peu digne de l'assemblée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000397","text":"Danton se plaignit de ce qu'il était faible et gouverné par sa femme; on répondit à ce reproche de faiblesse par la lettre du 3 septembre, et on aurait pu répondre encore en citant l'opposition que lui, Danton, avait rencontrée dans le conseil.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000398","text":"Cependant on passa à l'ordre du jour.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000399","text":"Pressé par les girondins et tous les gens de bien, Roland demeura au ministère.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000400","text":"«J'y reste, écrivit-il noblement à l'assemblée, puisque la calomnie m'y attaque, puisque des dangers m'y attendent, puisque la convention a paru désirer que j'y fusse encore.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000401","text":"Il est trop glorieux, ajouta-t-il en finissant sa lettre, qu'on n'ait eu à me reprocher que mon union avec le courage et la vertu.»","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000402","text":"L'assemblée se partagea ensuite en divers comités.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000403","text":"Elle créa un comité de surveillance composé de trente membres; un second de la guerre, de vingt-quatre; un troisième des comptes, de quinze; un quatrième de législation criminelle et civile, de quarante-huit; un cinquième des assignats, monnaies et finances, de quarante-deux.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000404","text":"Un sixième comité, plus important que tous les autres, fut chargé du principal objet pour lequel la convention était réunie, c'est-à-dire, de préparer un projet de constitution.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000405","text":"On le composa de neuf membres diversement célèbres, et presque tous choisis dans les intérêts du côté droit.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000406","text":"On est sans doute étonné de voir ce tribun si remuant, mais si peu spéculatif, placé dans ce comité tout philosophique, et il semble que le caractère de Robespierre, sinon ses talens, aurait dû lui valoir ce rôle.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000407","text":"Il est certain que Robespierre ambitionnait bien davantage cette distinction, et qu'il fut profondément blessé de ne pas l'obtenir.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000408","text":"On l'accorda de préférence à Danton, que son esprit naturel rendait propre à tout, et qu'aucun ressentiment profond ne séparait encore de ses collègues.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000409","text":"Ce fut cette composition du comité qui fit renvoyer si long-temps le travail de la constitution.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000410","text":"Le plus profond silence avait été observé à cet égard dans l'assemblée, et on en parlait partout, aux Jacobins, à la commune, dans tous les lieux particuliers ou publics, excepté seulement à la convention.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000411","text":"Des émigrés avaient été saisis les armes à la main, et on les conduisait à Paris pour leur appliquer les lois criminelles.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000412","text":"A ce sujet, une voix s'éleva (c'était la première), et demanda si, au lieu de s'occuper de ces coupables subalternes, on ne songerait pas à ces coupables plus élevés renfermés au Temple.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000413","text":"A ce mot, un profond silence régna dans l'assemblée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000414","text":"Barbaroux prit le premier la parole, et demanda qu'avant de savoir si la convention jugerait Louis XVI, on décidât si la convention serait corps judiciaire, car elle avait d'autres coupables à juger que ceux du Temple.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000415","text":"En élevant cette question, Barbaroux faisait allusion au projet d'instituer la convention en cour extraordinaire, pour juger elle-même _les agitateurs, les triumvirs_, etc.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000416","text":"Après quelques débats, la proposition fut renvoyée au comité de législation, pour examiner les questions auxquelles elle donnait naissance.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000417","text":"--ANECDOTE.--SECONDE LUTTE DES GIRONDINS AVEC LES MONTAGNARDS; LOUVET DÉNONCE ROBESPIERRE; RÉPONSE DE ROBESPIERRE; L'ASSEMBLÉE NE DONNE PAS SUITE A SON ACCUSATION.--PREMIÈRES PROPOSITIONS SUR LE PROCÈS DE LOUIS XVI.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000418","text":"Dans ce moment, la situation militaire de la France était bien changée. On touchait à la mi-octobre; déjà l'ennemi était repoussé de la Champagne et de la Flandre, et le sol étranger envahi sur trois points, le Palatinat, la Savoie et le comté de Nice.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000419","text":"On a vu les Prussiens se retirant du camp de la Lune, reprenant la route de l'Argonne, jonchant les défilés de morts et de malades, et n'échappant à une perte totale que par la négligence de nos généraux qui poursuivaient chacun un but différent.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000420","text":"Le duc de Saxe-Teschen n'avait pas mieux réussi dans son attaque sur les Pays-Bas.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000421","text":"Tandis que les Prussiens marchaient sur l'Argonne, ce prince, ne voulant pas rester en arrière, avait cru devoir essayer quelque entreprise éclatante.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000422","text":"Cependant, quoique notre frontière du Nord fût dégarnie, ses moyens n'étaient pas beaucoup plus grands que les nôtres, et il put à peine réunir quinze mille hommes avec un matériel médiocre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000423","text":"Feignant alors de fausses attaques sur toute la ligne des places fortes, il provoqua la déroute de l'un de nos petits camps, et se porta tout à coup sur Lille, pour essayer un siège que les plus grands généraux n'avaient pu exécuter avec de puissantes armées et un matériel considérable.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000424","text":"Il n'y a que la possibilité du succès qui justifie à la guerre les entreprises cruelles.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000425","text":"Le duc ne put aborder qu'un point de la place, et y établit des batteries d'obusiers, qui la bombardèrent pendant six jours consécutifs, et incendièrent plus de deux cents maisons.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000426","text":"On dit que l'archiduchesse Christine voulut assister elle-même à ce spectacle horrible.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000427","text":"S'il en est ainsi, elle ne put être témoin que de l'héroïsme des assiégés, et de l'inutilité des barbaries autrichiennes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000428","text":"Les Lillois, résistant avec une noble obstination, ne consentirent jamais à se rendre; et, le 8 octobre, tandis que les Prussiens abandonnaient l'Argonne, le duc Albert était obligé de quitter Lille.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000429","text":"Le général Labourdonnaie, arrivant de Soissons, Beurnonville, revenant de la Champagne, le forcèrent à s'éloigner rapidement de nos frontières, et la résistance des Lillois, publiée par toute la France, ne fit qu'augmenter l'enthousiasme général.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000430","text":"A peu près à la même époque, Custine tentait dans le Palatinat des entreprises hardies, mais d'un résultat plus brillant que solide.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000431","text":"Attaché à l'armée de Biron, qui campait le long du Rhin, il était placé avec dix-sept mille hommes à quelque distance de Spire.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000432","text":"La grande armée d'invasion n'avait que faiblement protégé ses derrières, en s'avançant dans l'intérieur de la France.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000433","text":"De faibles détachemens couvraient Spire, Worms et Mayence.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000434","text":"Custine s'en aperçut, marcha sur Spire, et y entra sans résistance le 30 septembre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000435","text":"Enhardi par le succès, il pénétra le 5 octobre dans Worms, sans rencontrer plus de difficultés, et obligea une garnison de deux mille sept cents hommes à mettre bas les armes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000436","text":"Il prit ensuite Franckenthal, et songea sur-le-champ à l'importante place de Mayence, qui était le point de retraite le plus important pour les Prussiens, et dans lequel ils avaient eu l'imprudence de ne laisser qu'une médiocre garnison.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000437","text":"Custine, avec dix-sept mille hommes et sans matériel, ne pouvait tenter un siège, mais il essaya d'un coup de main.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000438","text":"Les idées qui avaient soulevé la France agitaient toute l'Allemagne, et particulièrement les villes à université; Mayence en était une, et Custine y pratiqua des intelligences.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000439","text":"Il s'approcha des murs, s'en éloigna sur la fausse nouvelle de l'arrivée d'un corps autrichien, s'y reporta de nouveau, et, faisant de grands mouvemens, trompa l'ennemi sur la force de son armée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000440","text":"Le projet de capitulation fut fortement appuyé par les partisans des Français, et le 21 octobre les portes furent ouvertes à Custine.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000441","text":"La garnison mit bas les armes, excepté huit cents Autrichiens, qui rejoignirent la grande armée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000442","text":"La nouvelle de ces succès se répandit avec éclat, et causa une sensation extraordinaire.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000443","text":"Ils avaient sans doute bien peu coûté, ils étaient bien peu méritoires, comparés à la constance des Lillois et au magnanime sang-froid déployé à Sainte-Menehould; mais on était enchanté de passer de la simple résistance à la conquête.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000444","text":"Jusque-là tout était bien de la part de Custine, si, appréciant sa position, il eût su terminer la campagne par un mouvement qui était possible et décisif.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000445","text":"En cet instant, les trois armées de Dumouriez, de Kellermann et de Custine, étaient, par la plus heureuse rencontre, placées de manière à détruire les Prussiens et à conquérir par une seule marche toute la ligne du Rhin jusqu'à la mer.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000446","text":"Si Dumouriez, moins préoccupé d'une autre idée, eût gardé Kellermann sous ses ordres, et eût poursuivi les Prussiens avec ses quatre-vingt mille hommes; si en même temps Custine, descendant le Rhin de Mayence à Coblentz, se fût jeté sur leurs derrières, on les aurait accablés infailliblement.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000447","text":"Suivant ensuite le cours du Rhin jusqu'en Hollande, on prenait le duc Albert à revers, on l'obligeait à déposer les armes ou à se faire jour, et tous les Pays-Bas étaient soumis.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000448","text":"Trèves et Luxembourg, compris dans la ligne que nous avions décrite, tombaient nécessairement; tout était France jusqu'au Rhin, et la campagne se trouvait terminée en un mois.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000449","text":"Le génie abondait chez Dumouriez, mais ses idées avaient pris un autre cours.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000450","text":"Brûlant de retourner en Belgique, il ne songeait qu'à y marcher directement, pour secourir Lille et pousser de front le duc Albert.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000451","text":"Il laissa donc Kellermann seul à la poursuite des Prussiens.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000452","text":"Celui-ci pouvait encore se porter sur Coblentz, en passant entre Luxembourg et Trèves, tandis que Custine descendrait de Mayence.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000453","text":"Mais Kellermann, peu entreprenant, ne présuma pas assez de ses troupes, qui paraissaient harassées, et se cantonna autour de Metz.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000454","text":"Custine, de son côté, voulant se rendre indépendant et faire des incursions brillantes, n'avait aucune envie de se joindre à Kellermann et de se renfermer dans la limite du Rhin.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000455","text":"Il ne pensa donc jamais à venir à Coblentz.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000456","text":"Ainsi fut négligé ce beau plan, si bien saisi et développé par le plus grand de nos historiens militaires.[1]","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000457","text":"Custine, avec de l'esprit, était hautain, emporté et inconséquent.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000458","text":"Il tendait surtout à se rendre indépendant de Biron et de tout autre général, et il eut l'idée de conquérir autour de lui.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000459","text":"Prendre Manheim, l'exposait à violer la neutralité de l'électeur palatin, ce qui lui était défendu par le conseil exécutif; il songea donc à désemparer le Rhin pour s'avancer en Allemagne.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000460","text":"Francfort, placé sur le Mein, lui sembla une proie digne d'envie, et il résolut de s'y porter.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000461","text":"Cependant cette ville libre, commerçante, toujours neutre dans les diverses guerres, et bien disposée pour les Français, ne méritait pas cette fâcheuse préférence.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000462","text":"N'étant point défendue, il était facile d'y entrer, mais difficile de s'y maintenir, et par conséquent inutile de l'occuper.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000463","text":"Il leva des contributions, indisposa les habitans, dont il fit des ennemis pour les Français, et s'exposa, en se jetant ainsi sur le Mein, à être coupé du Rhin, ou par les Prussiens, s'ils fussent remontés jusqu'à Bingen, ou par l'électeur palatin, si, rompant la neutralité, il fût sorti de Manheim.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000464","text":"La nouvelle de ces courses sur le territoire ennemi continua de causer une grande joie à la France, qui était tout étonnée de conquérir, quelques jours après avoir tant craint d'être conquise elle-même.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000465","text":"Les Prussiens alarmés jetèrent un pont volant sur le Rhin, pour remonter le long de la rive droite, et chasser les Français.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000466","text":"Heureusement pour Custine, ils mirent douze jours à passer le fleuve.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000467","text":"Le découragement, les maladies, et la séparation des Autrichiens, avaient réduit cette armée à cinquante mille hommes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000468","text":"Clerfayt, avec ses dix-huit mille Autrichiens, avait suivi le mouvement général de nos troupes vers la Flandre, et se portait au secours du duc Albert.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000469","text":"Le corps des émigrés avait été licencié, et cette brillante milice s'était réunie au corps de Condé, ou avait passé à la solde étrangère.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000470","text":"Tandis que ces événements se passaient à la frontière du Nord et du Rhin, nous remportions d'autres avantages sur la frontière des Alpes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000471","text":"Montesquiou, placé à l'armée du Midi, envahissait la Savoie et faisait occuper le comté de Nice par un de ses lieutenans.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000472","text":"Ce général, qui avait fait voir dans la constituante toutes les lumières d'un homme d'état, et qui n'eut pas le temps de montrer les qualités d'un militaire, dont on assure qu'il était doué, avait été mandé à la barre de la législative pour rendre compte de sa conduite, accusée de trop de lenteur.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000473","text":"Il était parvenu à convaincre ses accusateurs que ses retards tenaient au défaut de moyens, et non au manque de zèle, et il était retourné aux Alpes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000474","text":"Cependant il appartenait à la première génération révolutionnaire, et se trouvait ainsi incompatible avec la nouvelle.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000475","text":"Mandé encore une fois, il allait être destitué, lorsqu'on apprit enfin son entrée en Savoie.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000476","text":"Sa destitution fut alors suspendue, et on lui laissa continuer sa conquête.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000477","text":"D'après le plan conçu par Dumouriez, lorsqu'en qualité de ministre des affaires étrangères il régissait à la fois la diplomatie et la guerre, la France devait pousser ses armées jusqu'à ses frontières naturelles, le Rhin et la haute chaîne des Alpes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000478","text":"Pour cela, il fallait conquérir la Belgique, la Savoie et Nice.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000479","text":"La France avait ainsi l'avantage, en rentrant dans les principes naturels de sa politique, de ne dépouiller, que les deux seuls ennemis qui lui fissent la guerre, la maison d'Autriche et la cour de Turin.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000480","text":"C'est de ce plan, manqué en avril dans la Belgique, et différé jusqu'ici dans la Savoie, que Montesquiou allait exécuter sa partie.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000481","text":"Il forma aussitôt une assemblée de Savoisiens, pour y faire délibérer sur une question qui ne pouvait pas être douteuse, cette de la réunion à la France.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000482","text":"Au même instant, Anselme, renforcé de six mille Marseillais, qu'il avait demandés comme auxiliaires, s'était approché du Var, torrent inégal, comme tous ceux qui descendent des hautes montagnes, tour à tour immense ou desséché, et ne pouvant pas même recevoir un pont fixe.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000483","text":"Anselme passa très hardiment le Var, et occupa Nice que le comte Saint-André venait d'abandonner, et où les magistrats l'avaient pressé d'entrer pour arrêter les désordres de la populace, qui se livrait à d'affreux pillages.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000484","text":"Les troupes sardes se rejetèrent vers les hautes vallées; Anselme les poursuivit; mais il s'arrêta devant un poste redoutable, celui de Saorgio, dont il ne put jamais chasser les Piémontais.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000485","text":"Pendant ce temps, l'escadre de l'amiral Truguet, combinant ses mouvemens avec ceux du général Anselme, avait obtenu la reddition de Villefranche, et s'était portée devant la petite principauté d'Oneille.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000486","text":"Beaucoup de corsaires trouvaient ordinairement un asile dans ce port, et par cette raison, il n'était pas inutile de le réduire.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000487","text":"Mais, tandis qu'un canot français s'avançait pour parlementer, plusieurs hommes furent, en violation du droit des gens, tués par une décharge générale.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000488","text":"L'amiral, embossant alors ses vaisseaux devant le port, l'écrasa de ses feux, y débarqua ensuite quelques troupes, qui saccagèrent la ville, et firent un grand carnage des moines qui s'y trouvaient en grand nombre, et qui étaient, dit-on, les instigateurs de ce manque de foi.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000489","text":"Telle est la rigueur des lois militaires, et la malheureuse ville d'Oneille les subit sans aucune miséricorde.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000490","text":"Après cette expédition, l'escadre française retourna devant Nice, où Anselme, séparé par les crues du Var du reste de son armée, se trouvait dangereusement compromis.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000491","text":"Cependant, en se gardant bien contre le poste de Saorgio, et en ménageant les habitans plus qu'il ne le faisait, sa position était tenable, et il pouvait conserver sa conquête.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000492","text":"Sur ces entrefaites, Montesquiou s'avançait de Chambéry sur Genève, et allait se trouver en présence de la Suisse, très diversement disposée pour les Français, et qui prétendait voir dans l'invasion de la Savoie un danger pour sa neutralité.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000493","text":"Les sentimens des cantons étaient très partagés à notre égard.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000494","text":"Toutes les républiques aristocratiques condamnaient notre révolution.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000495","text":"Berne surtout, et son avoyer Stinger, la détestaient profondément, et d'autant plus que le pays de Vaud, si opprimé, la chérissait davantage.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000496","text":"Le parti modéré l'emporta néanmoins, et on résolut une neutralité armée.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000497","text":"Le canton de Berne, plus irrité et plus défiant, porta un corps d'armée à Nyon, et, sous le prétexte d'une demande des magistrats de Genève, plaça garnison dans cette ville.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000498","text":"D'après les anciens traités, Genève, en cas dé guerre entre la France et la Savoie, ne devait recevoir garnison ni de l'une ni de l'autre puissance.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000499","text":"Notre envoyé en sortit aussitôt, et le conseil exécutif, poussé par Clavière, autrefois exilé de Genève, et jaloux d'y faire entrer la révolution, ordonna à Montesquiou de faire exécuter les traités.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000500","text":"De plus, on lui enjoignit de mettre lui-même garnison dans la place, c'est-à-dire d'imiter la faute reprochée aux Bernois.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000501","text":"Montesquiou sentait d'abord qu'il n'avait pas actuellement les moyens de prendre Genève, et ensuite qu'en rompant la neutralité et en se mettant en guerre avec la Suisse, on ouvrait l'est de la France, et on découvrait le flanc droit de notre défensive.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000502","text":"Il résolut d'un côté d'intimider Genève, tandis que de l'autre il tâcherait de faire entendre raison au conseil exécutif.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000503","text":"Il demanda donc hautement la sortie des troupes bernoises, et essaya de persuader au ministère français qu'on ne pouvait exiger davantage.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000504","text":"Son projet était, en cas d'extrémité, de bombarder Genève, et de se porter par une marche hardie sur le canton de Vaud, pour le mettre en révolution.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000505","text":"Genève consentit à la sortie des troupes bernoises, à condition que Montesquiou se retirerait à dix lieues, ce qu'il exécuta sur-le-champ.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000506","text":"Cette négociation, prolongée par la distance des lieux, n'était pas encore près de finir, quoiqu'on fût à la fin d'octobre.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000507","text":"Tel était donc, en octobre 1792, depuis Dunkerque jusqu'à Bâle, et depuis Bâle jusqu'à Nice, l'état de nos armes.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000508","text":"La frontière de la Champagne était délivrée de la grande invasion; les troupes se portaient de cette province vers la Flandre, pour secourir Lille et envahir la Belgique.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000509","text":"Kellermann prenait ses quartiers en Lorraine.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000510","text":"Biron campait toujours le long du Rhin.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000511","text":"Montesquiou, maître de la Savoie par la retraite des Piémontais au-delà des Alpes, et préservé de nouvelles attaques par les neiges, avait à décider la question de la neutralité suisse ou par les armes ou par des négociations.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000512","text":"Enfin Anselme, maître de Nice, et soutenu, par une escadre, pouvait résister dans sa position malgré les crues du Var, et malgré les Piémontais groupés au-dessus de lui dans le poste de Saorgio.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000513","text":"Tandis que la guerre allait se transporter de la Champagne dans la Belgique, Dumouriez avait demandé la permission de se rendre à Paris pour deux ou trois jours seulement, afin de concerter avec les ministres l'invasion des Pays-Bas et le plan général de toutes les opérations militaires.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000514","text":"Ses ennemis répandirent qu'il venait se faire applaudir, et qu'il quittait le soin de son commandement pour une frivole satisfaction de vanité.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000515","text":"Ces reproches étaient exagérés, car le commandement de Dumouriez ne souffrait pas de cette absence, et de simples marches de troupes pouvaient se faire sans lui.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000516","text":"Sa présence au contraire devait être fort utile au conseil pour la détermination d'un plan général, et d'ailleurs on pouvait lui pardonner une impatience de gloire, si générale chez les hommes, et si excusable quand elle ne nuit pas à des devoirs.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000517","text":"Il arriva le 11 octobre à Paris.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000518","text":"Sa position était embarrassante, car il ne pouvait se trouver bien avec aucun des deux partis.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000519","text":"La violence des jacobins lui répugnait, et il avait rompu avec les girondins, en les expulsant quelques mois auparavant du ministère.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000520","text":"Cependant, fort bien accueilli dans toute la Champagne, il le fut encore mieux à Paris, surtout par les ministres et par Roland lui-même, qui mettait ses ressentimens personnels au néant, quand il s'agissait de la chose publique.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000521","text":"Il se présenta le 12 à la convention.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000522","text":"A peine l'eut-on annoncé, que des applaudissemens mêlés d'acclamations s'élevèrent de toutes parts.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000523","text":"Il prononça un discours simple, énergique, où était brièvement retracée toute la campagne de l'Argonne, et où ses troupes et Kellermann lui-même étaient traités avec les plus grands éloges.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000524","text":"Son état-major présenta ensuite un drapeau pris sur les émigrés, et l'offrit à l'assemblée comme un monument de la vanité de leurs projets.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000525","text":"Aussitôt après, les députés se hâtèrent de l'entourer, et on leva la séance pour donner un libre cours aux félicitations.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000526","text":"Ce furent surtout les nombreux députés de la Plaine, les _impartiaux_, comme on les appelait, qui, n'ayant à lui reprocher ni rupture ni tiédeur révolutionnaire, lui témoignèrent le plus vif et le plus sincère empressement.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000527","text":"Les girondins ne restèrent pas en arrière; cependant, soit par la faute de Dumouriez, soit par la leur, la réconciliation ne fut pas entière, et on put apercevoir entre eux un reste de froideur.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000528","text":"Après la convention, restait à visiter les jacobins, et cette puissance était alors devenue si imposante, que le général victorieux ne pouvait se dispenser de lui rendre hommage.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000529","text":"C'est là que l'opinion en fermentation formait tous ses projets et rendait tous ses arrêts.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000530","text":"S'agissait-il d'une loi importante, d'une haute question politique, d'une grande mesure révolutionnaire, les jacobins, toujours plus prompts, se hâtaient d'ouvrir la discussion et de donner leur avis.","author":"Pali Canon","source":"Buddhism in Translations — Warren (1896)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000531","text":"Produced by Charles Keller and David Widger","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000532","text":"By Elbridge S. {Streeter} Brooks","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000533","text":"[This was orginally done on the 400th Anniversary of 1492 as was the great Columbian Exposition in Chicago. Interesting how our heroes have all been de-canonized in the interest of Political Correctitude--Comments by Michael S. Hart]","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000534","text":"The True Story of Christopher Columbus\" will be followed by the \"true story\" of others who have left names for us to honor and revere, who have made the world better because they lived, and who have helped to make and to develop American freedom, strength and progress.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000535","text":"It will be the endeavor to have all these presented in the simple, straightforward, earnest way that appeals to children, and shows how the hero can be the man, and the man the hero. E. S. B.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000536","text":"THE TRUE STORY OF CHRISTOPHER COLUMBUS","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000537","text":"Men who do great things are men we all like to read about.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000538","text":"This is the story of Christopher Columbus, the man who discovered America.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000539","text":"He lived four hundred years ago.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000540","text":"When he was a little boy he lived in Genoa.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000541","text":"It was a beautiful city in the northwestern part of the country called Italy.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000542","text":"The mountains were behind it; the sea was in front of it, and it was so beautiful a place that the people who lived there called it \"Genoa the Superb.\" Christopher Columbus was born in this beautiful city of Genoa in the year 1446, at number 27 Ponticello Street.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000543","text":"He was a bright little fellow with a fresh-looking face, a clear eye and golden hair.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000544","text":"His father's name was Domenico Columbus; his mother's name was Susanna.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000545","text":"He cleaned and straightened out the snarled-up wool that was cut from the sheep so as to make it ready to be woven into cloth.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000546","text":"Christopher helped his father do this when he grew strong enough, but he went to school, too, and learned to read and write and to draw maps and charts.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000547","text":"These charts were maps of the sea, to show the sailors where they could steer without running on the rocks and sand, and how to sail safely from one country to another.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000548","text":"This world was not as big then as it is now--or, should say, people did not know it was as big.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000549","text":"Most of the lands that Columbus had studied about in school, and most of the people he had heard about, were in Europe and parts of Asia and Africa.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000550","text":"The city of Genoa where Columbus lived was a very busy and a very rich city.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000551","text":"It was on the Mediterranean Sea, and many of the people who lived there were sailors who went in their ships on voyages to distant lands.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000552","text":"They sailed to other places on the Mediterranean Sea, which is a very large body of water, you know, and to England, to France, to Norway, and even as far away as the cold northern island of Iceland.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000553","text":"This was thought to be a great journey.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000554","text":"The time in which Columbus lived was not as nice a time as is this in which you live.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000555","text":"People were always quarreling and fighting about one thing or another, and the sailors who belonged to one country would try to catch and steal the ships or the things that belonged to the sailors or the storekeepers of another country.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000556","text":"This is what we call piracy, and a pirate, you know, is thought to be a very wicked man.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000557","text":"But when Columbus lived, men did not think it was so very wicked to be a sort of half-way pirate, although they did know that they would be killed if they were caught.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000558","text":"So almost every sailor was about half pirate.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000559","text":"Every boy who lived near the seashore and saw the ships and the sailors, felt as though he would like to sail away to far-off lands and see all the strange sights and do all the brave things that the sailors told about.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000560","text":"Many of them even said they would like to be pirates and fight with other sailors, and show how strong and brave and plucky they could be.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000561","text":"Columbus was one of these. He was what is called an adventurous boy. He did not like to stay quietly at home with his father and comb out the tangled wool. He thought it would be much nicer to sail away to sea and be a brave captain or a rich merchant.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000562","text":"When he was about fourteen years old he really did go to sea.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000563","text":"There was a captain of a sailing vessel that sometimes came to Genoa who had the same last name--Columbus.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000564","text":"He was no relation, but the little Christopher somehow got acquainted with him among the wharves of Genoa.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000565","text":"Perhaps he had run on errands for him, or helped him with some of the sea-charts he knew so well how to draw.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000566","text":"At any rate he sailed away with this Captain Columbus as his cabin boy, and went to the wars with him and had quite an exciting life for a boy.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000567","text":"Sailors are very fond of telling big stories about their own adventures or about far-off lands and countries. Columbus, listened to many of these sea-stories, and heard many wonderful things about a very rich land away to the East that folks called Cathay.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000568","text":"If you look in your geographies you will not find any such place on the map as Cathay, but you will find China, and that was what men in the time of Columbus called Cathay.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000569","text":"They told very big stories about this far-off Eastern land.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000570","text":"They said its kings lived in golden houses, that they were covered with pearls and diamonds, and that everybody there was so rich that money was as plentiful as the stones in the street.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000571","text":"This, of course, made the sailors and storekeepers, who were part pirate, very anxious to go to Cathay and get some of the gold and jewels and spices and splendor for themselves.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000572","text":"But Cathay was miles and miles away from Italy and Spain and France and England.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000573","text":"It was away across the deserts and mountains and seas and rivers, and they had to give it up because they could not sail there.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000574","text":"At last a man whose name was Marco Polo, and who was a very brave and famous traveler, really did go there, in spite of all the trouble it took.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000575","text":"And when he got back his stories were so very surprising that men were all the more anxious to find a way to sail in their ships to Cathay and see it for themselves.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000576","text":"Just look at your map again and see what a long, long voyage it would be to sail from Spain and around Africa to India, China and Japan.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000577","text":"It is such a long sail that, as you know, the Suez Canal was dug some twenty years ago so that ships could sail through the Mediterranean Sea and out into the Indian Ocean, and not have to go away around Africa.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000578","text":"But when Columbus was a boy it was even worse than now, for no one really knew how long Africa was, or whether ships really could sail around it.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000579","text":"But Prince Henry said he knew they could, and he sent out ships to try.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000580","text":"He died before his Portuguese sailors, Bartholomew Diaz, in 1493, and Vasco de Gama, in 1497, at last did sail around it and got as far as \"the Indies.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000581","text":"So while Prince Henry was trying to see whether ships could sail around Africa and reach Cathay in that way, the boy Columbus was listening to the stories the sailors told and was wondering whether some other and easier way to Cathay might not be found.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000582","text":"When he was at school he had studied about a certain man named Pythagoras, who had lived in Greece thousands of years before he was born, and who had said that the earth was round \"like a ball or an orange.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000583","text":"As Columbus grew older and made maps and studied the sea, and read books and listened to what other people said, he began to believe that this man named Pythagoras might be right, and that the earth was round, though everybody declared it was flat.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000584","text":"If it is round, he said to himself, \"what is the use of trying to sail around Africa to get to Cathay?","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000585","text":"Why not just sail west from Italy or Spain and keep going right around the world until you strike Cathay?","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000586","text":"I believe it could be done,\" said Columbus.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000587","text":"By this time Columbus was a man.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000588","text":"He was thirty years old and was a great sailor.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000589","text":"He had been captain of a number of vessels; he had sailed north and south and east; he knew all about a ship and all about the sea.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000590","text":"But, though he was so good a sailor, when he said that he believed the earth was round, everybody laughed at him and said that he was crazy.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000591","text":"Why, how can the earth be round?\" they cried.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000592","text":"The water would all spill out if it were, and the men who live on the other side would all be standing on their heads with their feet waving in the air.\" And then they laughed all the harder.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000593","text":"But Columbus did not think it was anything to laugh at.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000594","text":"He believed it so strongly, and felt so sure that he was right, that he set to work to find some king or prince or great lord to let him have ships and sailors and money enough to try to find a way to Cathay by sailing out into the West and across the Atlantic Ocean.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000595","text":"Now this Atlantic Ocean, the western waves of which break upon our rocks and beaches, was thought in Columbus's day to be a dreadful place.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000596","text":"People called it the Sea of Darkness, because they did not know what was on the other side of it, or what dangers lay beyond that distant blue rim where the sky and water seem to meet, and which we call the horizon.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000597","text":"They thought the ocean stretched to the end of a flat world, straight away to a sort of \"jumping-off place,\" and that in this horrible jumping-off place were giants and goblins and dragons and monsters and all sorts of terrible things that would catch the ships and destroy them and the sailors.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000598","text":"So when Columbus said that he wanted to sail away toward this dreadful jumping-off place, the people said that he was worse than crazy. They said he was a wicked man and ought to be punished.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000599","text":"But they could not frighten Columbus.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000600","text":"He went from place to place trying to get the ships and sailors he wanted and was bound to have.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000601","text":"As you will see in the next chapter, he tried to get help wherever he thought it could be had.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000602","text":"He asked the people of his own home, the city of Genoa, where he had lived and played when a boy; he asked the people of the beautiful city that is built in the sea--Venice; he tried the king of Portugal, the king of England, the king of France the king and queen of Spain.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000603","text":"But for a long time nobody cared to listen to such a wild and foolish and dangerous plan--to go to Cathay by the way of the Sea of Darkness and the Jumping-off place.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000604","text":"You would never get there alive, they said.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000605","text":"And his hair grew white while he waited, though he was not yet an old man.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000606","text":"He had thought and worked and hoped so much that he began to look like an old man when he was forty years old.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000607","text":"But still he would never say that perhaps he was wrong, after all.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000608","text":"He said he knew he was right, and that some day he should find the Indies and sail to Cathay.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000609","text":"CHAPTER II. WHAT PEOPLE THOUGHT OF THE IDEA.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000610","text":"I do not wish you to think that Columbus was the first man to say that the earth was round, or the first to sail to the West over the Atlantic Ocean.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000611","text":"Other men had said that they believed the earth was round; other men had sailed out into the Atlantic Ocean.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000612","text":"But no sailor who believed the earth was round had ever yet tried to prove that it was by crossing the Atlantic.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000613","text":"So, you see, Columbus was really the first man to say, I believe the earth is round and I will show you that it is by sailing to the lands that are on the other side of the earth.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000614","text":"He even figured out how far it was around the world.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000615","text":"Your geography, you know, tells you now that what is called the circumference of the earth--that is, a straight line drawn right around it--is nearly twenty-five thousand miles.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000616","text":"Columbus had figured it up pretty carefully and he thought it was about twenty thousand miles.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000617","text":"If I could start from Genoa, he said, and walk straight ahead until I got back to Genoa again, I should walk about twenty thousand miles.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000618","text":"Cathay, he thought, would take up so much land on the other side of the world that, if he went west instead of east, he would only need to sail about twenty-five hundred or three thousand miles.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000619","text":"If you have studied your geography carefully you will see what a mistake he made.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000620","text":"It is really about twelve thousand miles from Spain to China (or Cathay as he called it). But America is just about three thousand miles from Spain, and if you read all this story you will see how Columbus's mistake really helped him to discover America.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000621","text":"I have told you that Columbus had a longing to do something great from the time when, as a little boy, he had hung around the wharves in Genoa and looked at the ships sailing east and west and talked with the sailors and wished that he could go to sea.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000622","text":"Perhaps what he had learned at school--how some men said that the earth was round--and what he had heard on the wharves about the wonders of Cathay set him to thinking and to dreaming that it might be possible for a ship to sail around the world without falling off.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000623","text":"At any rate, he kept on thinking and dreaming and longing until, at last, he began doing.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000624","text":"Some of the sailors sent out by Prince Henry of Portugal, of whom I have told you, in their trying to sail around Africa discovered two groups of islands out in the Atlantic that they called the Azores, or Isles of Hawks, and the Canaries, or Isles of Dogs.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000625","text":"When Columbus was in Portugal in 1470 he became acquainted with a young woman whose name was Philippa Perestrelo.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000626","text":"Now Philippa's father, before his death, had been governor of Porto Santo, one of the Azores, and Columbus and his wife went off there to live.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000627","text":"In the governor's house Columbus found a lot of charts and maps that told him about parts of the ocean that he had never before seen, and made him feel certain that he was right in saying that if he sailed away to the West he should find Cathay.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000628","text":"At that time there was an old man who lived in Florence, a city of Italy.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000629","text":"He was a great scholar and studied the stars and made maps, and was a very wise man.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000630","text":"Columbus knew what a wise old scholar Toscanelli was, for Florence is not very far from Genoa.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000631","text":"So while he was living in the Azores he wrote to this old scholar asking him what he thought about his idea that a man could sail around the world until he reached the land called the Indies and at last found Cathay.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000632","text":"Toscanelli wrote to Columbus saying that he believed his idea was the right one, and he said it would be a grand thing to do, if Columbus dared to try it.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000633","text":"Perhaps, he said, you can find all those splendid things that I know are in Cathay--the great cities with marble bridges, the houses of marble covered with gold, the jewels and the spices and the precious stones, and all the other wonderful and magnificent things.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000634","text":"I do not wonder you wish to try, he said, for if you find Cathay it will be a wonderful thing for you and for Portugal.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000635","text":"That settled it with Columbus. If this wise old scholar said he was right, he must be right. So he left his home in the Azores and went to Portugal. This was in 1475, and from that time on, for seventeen long years he was trying to get some king or prince to help him sail to the West to find Cathay.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000636","text":"But not one of the people who could have helped him, if they had really wished to, believed in Columbus.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000637","text":"As I told you, they said that he was crazy.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000638","text":"The king of Portugal, whose name was John, did a very unkind thing--I am sure you would call it a mean trick.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000639","text":"Columbus had gone to him with his story and asked for ships and sailors.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000640","text":"The king and his chief men refused to help him; but King John said to himself, perhaps there is something in this worth looking after and, if so, perhaps I can have my own people find Cathay and save the money that Columbus will want to keep for himself as his share of what he finds.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000641","text":"Then they hunted up Columbus and began to abuse him for getting them into such a scrape.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000642","text":"You might as well expect to find land in the sky, they said, as in those terrible waters.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000643","text":"And when, in this way, Columbus found out that King John had tried to use his ideas without letting him know anything about it, he was very angry.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000644","text":"His wife had died in the midst of this mean trick of the Portuguese king, and so, taking with him his little five-year-old son, Diego, he left Portugal secretly and went over into Spain.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000645","text":"Near the little town of Palos, in western Spain, is a green hill looking out toward the Atlantic.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000646","text":"Upon this hill stands an old building that, four hundred years ago, was used as a a convent or home for priests.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000647","text":"It was called the Convent of Rabida, and the priest at the head of it was named the Friar Juan Perez.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000648","text":"One autumn day, in the year 1484, Friar Juan Perez saw a dusty traveler with a little boy talking with the gate-keeper of the convent.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000649","text":"The stranger was so tall and fine-looking, and seemed such an interesting man, that Friar Juan went out and began to talk with him.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000650","text":"As they talked, the priest grew more and more interested in what Columbus said.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000651","text":"He invited him into the convent to stay for a few days, and he asked some other people--the doctor of Palos and some of the sea captains and sailors of the town--to come and talk with this stranger who had such a singular idea about sailing across the Atlantic.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000652","text":"It ended in Columbus's staying some months in Palos, waiting for a chance to go and see the king and queen. At last, in 1485, he set out for the Spanish court with a letter to a priest who was a friend of Friar Juan's, and who could help him to see the king and queen.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000653","text":"At that time the king and queen of Spain were fighting to drive out of Spain the people called the Moors.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000654","text":"These people came from Africa, but they had lived in Spain for many years and had once been a very rich and powerful nation.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000655","text":"They were not Spaniards; they were not Christians.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000656","text":"So all Spaniards and all Christians hated them and tried to drive them out of Europe.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000657","text":"The king and queen of Spain who were fighting the Moors were named Ferdinand and Isabella.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000658","text":"They were pretty good people as kings and queens went in those days, but they did a great many very cruel and very mean things, just as the kings and queens of those days were apt to do.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000659","text":"I am afraid we should not think they were very nice people nowadays.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000660","text":"We certainly should not wish our American boys and girls to look up to them as good and true and noble.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000661","text":"When Columbus first came to them, they were with the army in the camp near the city of Cordova.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000662","text":"The king and queen had no time to listen to what they thought were crazy plans, and poor Columbus could get no one to talk with him who could be of any help.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000663","text":"So he was obliged to go back to drawing maps and selling books to make enough money to support himself and his little Diego.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000664","text":"Columbus told his story. He said what he wished to do, and asked these learned men to say a good word for him to, Ferdinand and Isabella so that he could have the ships and sailors to sail to Cathay. But it was of no use.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000665","text":"those wise men cried in horror.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000666","text":"The world is not round; it is flat.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000667","text":"Your ships would tumble off the edge of the world and all the king's money and all the king's men would be lost.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000668","text":"No, no; go away; you must not trouble the queen or even mention such a ridiculous thing again.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000669","text":"But one or two thought it might be worth trying.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000670","text":"Cathay was a very rich country, and if this foolish fellow were willing to run the risk and did succeed, it would be a good thing for Spain, as the king and queen would need a great deal of money after the war with the Moors was over.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000671","text":"At any rate, it was a chance worth thinking about.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000672","text":"And so, although Columbus was dreadfully disappointed, he thought that if he had only a few friends at Court who were ready to say a good word for him he must not give up, but must try, try again. And so he staid in Spain.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000673","text":"CHAPTER III. HOW COLUMBUS GAINED A QUEEN FOR HIS FRIEND.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000674","text":"When you wish very much to do a certain thing it is dreadfully hard to be patient; it is harder still to have to wait.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000675","text":"The wars against the Moors were of much greater interest to the king and queen of Spain than was the finding of a new and very uncertain way to get to Cathay.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000676","text":"If it had not been for the patience and what we call the persistence of Columbus, America would never have been discovered--at least not in his time.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000677","text":"He staid in Spain. He grew poorer and, poorer. He was almost friendless. It seemed as if his great enterprise must be given up. But he never lost hope. He never stopped trying. Even when he failed he kept on hoping and kept on trying. He felt certain that sometime he should succeed.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000678","text":"As we have seen, he tried to interest the rulers of different countries, but with no success.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000679","text":"There was still left the king of France.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000680","text":"He would make one last attempt to win the king and queen of Spain to his side and if he failed with them he would try the last of the rulers of Western Europe, the king of France.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000681","text":"He followed the king and queen of Spain as they went from place to place fighting the Moors. He hoped that some day, when they wished to think of something besides fighting, they might think of him and the gold and jewels and spices of Cathay.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000682","text":"The days grew into months, the months to years, and still the war against the Moors kept on; and still Columbus waited for the chance that did not come.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000683","text":"At last he decided to make one more attempt before giving it up in Spain.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000684","text":"His money was gone; his friends were few; but he remembered his acquaintances at Palos and so he journeyed back to see once more his good friend Friar Juan Perez at the Convent of Rabida on the hill that looked out upon the Atlantic he was so anxious to cross.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000685","text":"It was in the month of November, 1491, that he went back to the Convent of Rabida. If he could not get any encouragement there, he was determined to stay in Spain no longer but to go away and try the king of France.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000686","text":"Once more he talked over the finding of Cathay with the priests and the sailors of Palos.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000687","text":"They saw how patient he was; how persistent he was; how he would never give up his ideas until he had tried them.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000688","text":"They were moved by his determination.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000689","text":"They began to believe in him more and more.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000690","text":"One of the principal sea captains of Palos was named Martin Alonso Pinzon.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000691","text":"This was a move in the right direction.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000692","text":"At once a messenger was sent to the splendid Spanish camp before the city of Granada, the last unconquered city of the Moors of Spain.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000693","text":"The king and queen of Spain had been so long trying to capture Granada that this camp was really a city, with gates and walls and houses.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000694","text":"Queen Isabella, who was in Santa Fe, after some delay, agreed to hear more about the crazy scheme of this persistent Genoese sailor, and the Friar Juan Perez was sent for.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000695","text":"He talked so well in behalf of his friend Columbus that the queen became still more interested.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000696","text":"She ordered Columbus to come and see her, and sent him sixty-five dollars to pay for a mule, a new suit of clothes and the journey to court.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000697","text":"About Christmas time, in the year 1491, Columbus, mounted upon his mule, rode into the Spanish camp before the city of Granada.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000698","text":"But even now, when he had been told to come, he had to wait.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000699","text":"Granada was almost captured; the Moors were almost conquered.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000700","text":"On the second of January, 1492, the Moorish king gave up the keys of his beloved city, and the great Spanish banner was hoisted on the highest tower of the Alhambra--the handsomest building in Granada and one of the most beautiful in the world.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000701","text":"The Moors were driven out of Spain and Columbus's chance had come.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000702","text":"So he appeared before Queen Isabella and her chief men and told them again of all his plans and desires.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000703","text":"The queen and her advisers sat in a great room in that splendid Alhambra I have told you of.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000704","text":"He did not believe in Columbus and did not wish to let him have either money, ships or sailors to lose in such a foolish way.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000705","text":"But as Columbus stood before her and talked so earnestly about how he expected to find the Indies and Cathay and what he hoped to bring away from there, Queen Isabella listened and thought the plan worth trying.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000706","text":"Then a singular thing happened.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000707","text":"You would think if you wished for something very much that you would give up a good deal for the sake of getting it.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000708","text":"Columbus had worked and waited for seventeen years.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000709","text":"He had never got what he wanted.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000710","text":"He was always being disappointed.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000711","text":"And yet, as he talked to the queen and told her what he wished to do, he said he must have so much as a reward for doing it that the queen and her chief men were simply amazed at his--well, what the boys to-day call \"cheek\"--that they would have nothing to do with him.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000712","text":"This man really is crazy, they said.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000713","text":"This poor Genoese sailor comes here without a thing except his very odd ideas, and almost \"wants the earth\" as a reward.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000714","text":"This is not exactly what they said, but it is what they meant.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000715","text":"His few friends begged him to be more modest.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000716","text":"Do not ask so much, they said, or you will get nothing.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000717","text":"I have worked and waited all these years, he replied.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000718","text":"I know just what I can do and just how much I can do for the king and queen of Spain.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000719","text":"They must pay me what I ask and promise what I say, or I will go somewhere else.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000720","text":"said the queen and her advisers.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000721","text":"And Columbus turned his back on what seemed almost his last hope, mounted his mule and rode away.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000722","text":"So two of them, whose names were Santangel and Quintanilla, rushed into the queen's room and begged her, if she wished to become the greatest queen in Christendom, to call back this wandering sailor, agree to his terms and profit by his labors.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000723","text":"What if he does ask a great deal?","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000724","text":"He has spent his life thinking his plan out; no wonder he feels that he ought to have a good share of what he finds.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000725","text":"What he asks is really small compared with what Spain will gain.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000726","text":"The war with the Moors has cost you ever so much; your money-chests are empty; Columbus will fill them up.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000727","text":"The people of Cathay are heathen; Columbus will help you make them Christian men.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000728","text":"The Indies and Cathay are full of gold and jewels; Columbus will bring you home shiploads of treasures.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000729","text":"Spain has conquered the Moors; Columbus will help you conquer Cathay.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000730","text":"In fact, they talked to Queen Isabella so strongly and so earnestly, that she, too, became excited over this chance for glory and riches that she had almost lost, Quick!","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000731","text":"If King Ferdinand cannot or will not take the risk, I, the queen, will do it all.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000732","text":"do not let the man get into France.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000733","text":"And without delay a royal messenger, mounted on a swift horse, was sent at full gallop to bring Columbus back.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000734","text":"All this time poor Columbus felt bad enough.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000735","text":"Now he must go away into a new land and do it all over again.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000736","text":"Just as he was riding across the little bridge called the Bridge of Pinos, some six miles from Granada, he heard the quick hoof-beats of a horse behind him.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000737","text":"It was a great spot for robbers, and Columbus felt of the little money he had in his traveling pouch, and wondered whether he must lose it all.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000738","text":"The queen bids you return to Granada.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000739","text":"Columbus hesitated. Ought he to trust this promise, he wondered. Put not your trust in princes, the verse in the Bible had said. If I go back I may only be put off and worried as I have been before. And yet, perhaps she means what she says. At any rate, I will go back and try once more.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000740","text":"So, on the little Bridge of Pinos, he turned his mule around and rode back to Granada.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000741","text":"And, sure enough, when he saw Queen Isabella she agreed to all that he asked.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000742","text":"For his part (and this was because of the offer of his friend at Palos, Captain Pinzon) he agreed to pay one eighth of all the expenses of this expedition and of all new enterprises, and was to have one eighth of all the profits from them.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000743","text":"So Columbus had his wish at last. The queen's men figured up how much money they could let him have; they called him \"Don Christopher Columbus,\" \"Your Excellency\" and \"Admiral,\" and at once he set about getting ready for his voyage.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000744","text":"CHAPTER IV. HOW THE ADMIRAL SAILED AWAY.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000745","text":"The agreement made between Columbus and the king and queen of Spain was signed on the seventeenth of April, 1492. But it was four months before he was quite ready to sail away.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000746","text":"He selected the town of Palos as the place to sail from, because there, as you know, Captain Pinzon lived; there, too, he had other acquaintances, so that he supposed it would be easy to get the sailors he needed for his ships. But in this he was greatly mistaken.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000747","text":"As soon as the papers had been signed that held the queen to her promise, Columbus set off for Palos. He stopped at the Convent of Rabida to tell the Friar Juan Perez how thankful he was to him for the help the good priest had given him, and how everything now looked promising and successful.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000748","text":"The town of Palos, as you can see from your map of Spain, is situated at the mouth of the river Tinto on a little bay in the southwestern part of Spain, not far from the borders of Portugal.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000749","text":"To-day the sea has gone away from it so much that it is nearly high and dry; but four hundred years ago it was quite a seaport, when Spain did not have a great many sea towns on the Atlantic coast.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000750","text":"At the time of Columbus's voyage the king and queen of Spain were angry with the port of Palos for something its people had done that was wrong--just what this was we do not know.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000751","text":"But to punish the town, and because Columbus wished to sail from there, the king and queen ordered that Palos should pay them a fine for their wrong-doing.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000752","text":"And this fine was to lend the king and queen of Spain, for one year, without pay, two sailing vessels of the kind called caravel's, armed and equipped \"for the service of the crown\"--that is, for the use of the king and queen of Spain, in the western voyage that Columbus was to make.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000753","text":"When Columbus called together the leading people of Palos to meet him in the church of St.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000754","text":"George and hear the royal commands, they came; but at first they did not understand just what they must do.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000755","text":"But when they knew that they must send two of their ships and some of their sailing men on this dreadful voyage far out upon the terrible Sea of Darkness, they were terribly distressed.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000756","text":"They would obey the commands of the king and queen and furnish the two ships, but as for sailing off with this crazy sea captain--that they would not do.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000757","text":"Then the king's officers went to work.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000758","text":"They seized some sailors (impressed is the word for this), and made them go; they took some from the jails, and gave them their freedom as a reward for going; they begged and threatened and paid in advance, and still it was hard to get enough men for the two ships.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000759","text":"Then Captain Pinzon, who had promised Columbus that he would join him, tried his hand.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000760","text":"He added a third ship to the Admiral's \"fleet.\" He made big promises to the sailors, and worked for weeks, until at last he was able to do what even the royal commands could not do, and a crew of ninety men was got together to man the three vessels.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000761","text":"The names of these three vessels were the Capitana (changed before it sailed to the Santa Maria), the Pinta and the Nina or Baby.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000762","text":"Captain de la Cosa commanded the Santa Maria, Captain Martin Alonso Pinzon the Pinta and his brother, Captain Vincent Pinzon, the Nina.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000763","text":"The Santa Maria was the largest of the three vessels; it was therefore selected as the leader of the fleet--the flag-ship, as it is called--and upon it sailed the commander of the expedition, the Admiral Don Christopher Columbus.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000764","text":"When we think of a voyage across the Atlantic nowadays, we think of vessels as large as the big three-masted ships or the great ocean steamers--vessels over six hundred feet long and fifty feet wide.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000765","text":"But these \"ships\" of Columbus were not really ships.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000766","text":"They were hardly larger than the \"fishing smacks\" that sail up and down our coast to-day.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000767","text":"Some of them were not so large.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000768","text":"The Santa Maria was, as I have told you, the largest of the three, and she was only sixty-three feet long, twenty feet wide and ten and a half feet deep.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000769","text":"Just measure this out on the ground and see how small, after all, the Admiral's \"flag-ship\" really was.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000770","text":"The Pinta was even smaller than this, while the little Nina was hardly anything more than a good-sized sail boat.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000771","text":"Do you wonder that the poor people of Palos and the towns round about were frightened when they thought of their fathers and brothers and sons putting out to sea, on the great ocean they had learned to dread so much, in such shaky little boats as these?","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000772","text":"But finally the vessels were ready. The crews were selected. The time had come to go. Most of the sailors were Spanish men from the towns near to the sea, but somehow a few who were not Spaniards joined the crew.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000773","text":"One of the first men to land in America from one of the ships of Columbus was an Irishman named William, from the County Galway.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000774","text":"And another was an Englishman named either Arthur Laws or Arthur Larkins.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000775","text":"The Spanish names for both these men look very queer, and only a wise scholar who digs among names and words could have found out what they really were.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000776","text":"But such a one did find it out, and it increases our interest in the discovery of America to know that some of our own northern blood--the Irishman and the Englishman--were in the crews of Columbus.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000777","text":"The Admiral Columbus was so sure he was going to find a rich and civilized country, such as India and Cathay were said to be, that he took along on his ships the men he would need in such places as he expected to visit and among such splendid people as he was sure he should meet.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000778","text":"He took along a lawyer to make out all the forms and proclamations and papers that would have to be sent by the Admiral to the kings and princes he expected to visit; he had a secretary and historian to write out the story of what he should find and what he should do.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000779","text":"There was a learned Jew, named Louis, who could speak almost a dozen languages, and who could, of course, tell him what the people of Cathay and Cipango and the Indies were talking about.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000780","text":"Some scholars have said that it cost about two hundred and thirty thousand dollars to fit out this expedition.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000781","text":"I do not think it cost nearly so much.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000782","text":"We do know that Queen Isabella gave sixty-seven thousand dollars to help pay for it.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000783","text":"Some people, however, reckoning the old Spanish money in a different way, say that what Queen Isabella gave toward the expedition was not over three or four thousand dollars of our money.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000784","text":"Perhaps as much more was borrowed from King Ferdinand, although he was to have no share in the enterprise in which Queen Isabella and Columbus were partners.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000785","text":"It was just an hour before sunrise on Friday, the third of August, 1492, that the three little ships hoisted their anchors and sailed away from the port of Palos.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000786","text":"I suppose it was a very sorry and a very exciting morning in Palos.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000787","text":"The people probably crowded down on the docks, some of them sad and sorrowful, some of them restless and curious.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000788","text":"Their fathers and brothers and sons and acquaintances were going--no one knew where, dragged off to sea by a crazy old Italian sailor who thought there was land to be found somewhere beyond the Jumping-off place.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000789","text":"They were certain that nothing but dreadful goblins and horrible monsters lived off there to the West, just waiting to devour or destroy the poor sailors when these three little ships should tumble over the edge.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000790","text":"But how different Columbus must have felt as he stepped, into the rowboat that took him off to his \"flag-ship,\" the Santa Maria.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000791","text":"He had ships and sailors under his command, and was about to sail away to discover great and wonderful things.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000792","text":"He who had been so poor that he could hardly buy his own dinner, was now called Don and Admiral.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000793","text":"He had a queen for his friend and helper.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000794","text":"He was given a power that only the richest and noblest could hope for.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000795","text":"But more than all, he was to have the chance he had wished and worked for so long.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000796","text":"He was to find the Indies; he was to see Cathay; he was to have his share in all the wealth he should discover and bring away.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000797","text":"The son of the poor wool-weaver of Genoa was to be the friend of kings and princes; the cabin boy of a pirate was now Admiral of the Seas and Governor of the Colonies of Spain!","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000798","text":"Do you wonder that he felt proud?","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000799","text":"The westward voyage to those wonderful lands, the Indies and Cathay, had at last begun.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000800","text":"CHAPTER V. HOW THEY FARED ON THE SEA OF DARKNESS.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000801","text":"Did you ever set out, in the dark, to walk with your little brother or sister along a road you did not know much about or had never gone over before?","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000802","text":"It was not an easy thing to do, was it?","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000803","text":"And how did your little brother or sister feel when it was known that you were not just certain whether you were right or not?","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000804","text":"Do you remember what the Bible says about the blind leading the blind?","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000805","text":"It was much the same with Columbus when he set out from Palos to sail over an unknown sea to find the uncertain land of Cathay.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000806","text":"He had his own idea of the way there, but no one in all his company had ever sailed it, and he himself was not sure about it.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000807","text":"And the sailors in the three ships were worse than little children.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000808","text":"They did not even have the confidence in their leader that your little brother or sister would probably have in you as you traveled that new road on a dark night.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000809","text":"It was almost another case of the blind leading the blind, was it not?","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000810","text":"Columbus first steered his ships to the south so as to reach the Canary Islands and commence his real westward voyage from there.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000811","text":"The Canary Islands, as you will see by looking in your geography, are made up of seven islands and lie off the northern corner of Africa, some sixty miles or so west of Morocco.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000812","text":"They were named Canaria by the Romans from the Latin canis, a dog, \"because of the multitude of dogs of great size\" that were found there.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000813","text":"The canary birds that sing so sweetly in your home come from these islands.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000814","text":"They had been known to the Spaniards and other European sailors of Columbus's day about a hundred years.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000815","text":"At the Canaries the troubles of Columbus commenced.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000816","text":"And he did have a lot of trouble before his voyage was over.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000817","text":"While near the island called the Grand Canary the rudder of the Pinta, in which Captain Alonso Pinzon sailed, somehow got loose, then broke and finally came off.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000818","text":"It was said that two of the Pinta's crew, who were really the owners of the vessel, broke the rudder on purpose, because they had become frightened at the thoughts of the perilous voyage, and hoped by damaging their vessel to be left behind.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000819","text":"But Columbus had no thought of doing any such thing.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000820","text":"He sailed to the island of Gomera, where he knew some people, and had the Pinta mended.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000821","text":"And while lying here with his fleet the great mountain on the island of Teneriffe, twelve thousand feet high, suddenly began to spit out flame and smoke.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000822","text":"It was, as of course you know, a volcano; but the poor frightened sailors did not know what set this mountain on fire, and they were scared almost out of their wits' and begged the Admiral to go back home.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000823","text":"And as they sailed away from Gomera some sailors told them that the king of Portugal was angry with Columbus because he had got his ships from the king and queen of Spain, and that he had sent out some of his war-ships to worry or capture Columbus.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000824","text":"But these, too, Columbus escaped, although not before his crews had grown terribly nervous for fear of capture.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000825","text":"At last they got away from the Canaries, and on Sunday, the ninth of September, 1492, with a fresh breeze filling their sails, the three caravels sailed away into the West.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000826","text":"And as the shores of Ferro, the very last of the Canary Islands, faded out of sight, the sailors burst into sighs and murmurings and tears, saying that now indeed they were sailing off--off--off--upon the awful Sea of Darkness and would never see land any more.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000827","text":"He made two records (or reckonings as they are called) of his sailing.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000828","text":"One of these records was a true one; this he kept for himself.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000829","text":"The other was a false one; this he kept to show his sailors.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000830","text":"So while they thought they were sailing slowly and that the ocean was not so very wide, Columbus knew from his own true record that they were getting miles and miles away from home.","author":"The Buddha","source":"Some Sayings of the Buddha — Woodward (1925)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000831","text":"There are two editions of this ebook in the Project Gutenberg collection. Various characteristics of each ebook are listed to aid in selecting the preferred file.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000832","text":"Click on any of the filenumbers below to quickly view each ebook.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000833","text":"27 1874, First Edition; illustrated.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000834","text":"107 1895, Second Edition, extensively revised by Thomas Hardy.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000835","text":"Description of Farmer Oak—An Incident Chapter II.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000836","text":"Night—The Flock—An Interior—Another Interior Chapter III.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000837","text":"A Girl on Horseback—Conversation Chapter IV.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"pali-ext-000838","text":"Gabriel’s Resolve—The Visit—The Mistake Chapter V.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:liberation","theme:liberation,impermanence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":fals